{"title_page": "Trade deal negotiation between the UK and EU", "text_new": "{{short description|The negotiation of a post-Brexit partnership and trade deal between the UK and the EU}}\n[[File:United Kingdom European Union Locator.svg|thumb|right|United Kingdom (green) and European Union (27 member states) orange]]\nThe '''Trade deal negotiation between the UK and EU''' is a post-[[Brexit]] negotiation between the parties that aims to achieve a [[free trade agreement|trade agreement]], to make trade easier than it would be without a trade deal. Such a deal might cover (or eliminate) both  [[tariff]] and [[non-tariff barriers to trade]].\n\nDuring the [[Brexit negotiations in 2017]], the sides agreed that trade negotiation could only start after the UK's withdrawal, because such negotiations could not happen when the UK still has a veto right within the EU.<ref>{{Cite news |url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/news/2017/04/29/eu-brexit-guidelines-document-really-means/ |title=EU Brexit guidelines: What's in the document, and what it really means |last=Foster |first=Peter |date=29 April 2017|newspaper=The Daily Telegraph |access-date=14 May 2017}}</ref> For this and other reasons, a [[transition period]] after Brexit day was defined to allow those negotiations. The transition period started on the first February 2020, in accordance with the [[Brexit withdrawal agreement|withdrawal agreement]]. The first deadline is the 31 December 2020, a deadline which can be extended for two years.<ref name=Euronews200211>{{Cite web|url=https://www.euronews.com/2020/02/11/brexit-draft-deal-first-of-many-hurdles-to-a-smooth-exit|title=Post-Brexit Guide: Where are we now? *latest updates*|first=Alasdair|last=Sandford|date=February 11, 2020|website=euronews}}</ref>. The British government has declared that it will not apply for any such extension.<ref>{{cite news| url= https://www.reuters.com/article/uk-britain-eu-johnson-transition/uk-will-not-extend-brexit-transition-period-johnsons-spokesman-idUSKBN1Z5139 | title = UK will not extend Brexit transition period - Johnson's spokesman | date =6 January 2020 | work = [[Reuters]] | accessdate=8 March 2020}}</ref>\n\nDuring Brexit negotiation, the UK clarified the only kind of trade deal the UK is interested is in, if any, is a [[Comprehensive Economic and Trade Agreement|Canadian style trade deal]]<ref name=\"politico-uk-may-not-like-\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.politico.eu/article/brexit-trade-deal-will-contain-financial-services-but-uk-may-not-like-it/|title=Brexit trade deal will contain financial services, but UK may not like it|first=Pierre|last=Brian\u00e7on|date=January 11, 2018|website=POLITICO}}</ref>, as documented in a famous [[Michel Barnier]] slide<ref name=\"15-12-2017\">{{cite web|url=https://ec.europa.eu/commission/sites/beta-political/files/slide_presented_by_barnier_at_euco_15-12-2017.pdf | title = Slide presented by Michel Barnier, European Commission Chief Negotiator, to the Heads of State and Government at the European Council (Article 50) on 15 December 2017| date=15 December 2017 | access-date = 8 March 2020| work= [[European Commission]]}}</ref>.\n\nAccording to an (unnamed) French government adviser speaking to journalist Pierre Brian\u00e7on of [[Politico.eu]], the sides have different approaches of this trade deal negotiation: \n* \"The UK wants to preserve as much as it can from the current situation. Their viewpoint is they\u2019re in, and what\u2019s being discussed is simply stripping away some components of the edifice\".<ref name=\"politico-uk-may-not-like-\" /> \n* given that the UK is legally out of the Union, the EU considers that each part of the relation has to be fully renegotiated bottom-up.<ref name=\"politico-uk-may-not-like-\" />\n\nUK needs a trade deal, because the UK is to be out of the [[European Single Market]] and [[European Union Customs Union]] as soon as the 1 January 2021.<ref name=bbc020320>{{Cite web|url=https://www.bbc.com/news/uk-47213842|title=Which countries does the UK do the most trade with?|first=Tom|last=Edgington|date=March 2, 2020|work=BBC News}}</ref> The trade deal would affect EU-UK trade, which accounts for 49% of international UK trade.<ref name=bbc020320 /> A Canadian style trade deal would offer the UK reduction on most of custom tariffs between the EU and UK, but without eliminating VAT, customs and [[phytosanitary]] checks.<ref name=bbc020320 /> The arrangements for its dominant [[financial services]] sector are of particular importance to the UK.<ref name=\"politico-uk-may-not-like-\" /> \n\n==EU-UK trade before Brexit==\n\nThe EU is the [[List of the largest trading partners of United Kingdom|UK's largest trading partner]], and in 2018 the bloc made up 45% of UK exports and 53% of UK imports.<ref name=lords7851 /> Outside EU, the biggest trading partner of the UK is USA, which in 2018 made up 19% of UK exports and 11% of UK imports.<ref name=lords7851>{{Cite web|url=https://researchbriefings.files.parliament.uk/documents/CBP-7851/CBP-7851.pdf|title=Statistics on UK-EU trade|last=Ward|first=Matthew|date=16 December 2019|website=House of Commons Library|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=5 March 2019}}</ref>\n\nFor the EU27, the UK is its second largest export market (after USA), and third largest import market (after China and USA).<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://trade.ec.europa.eu/doclib/docs/2013/december/tradoc_151969.pdf|title=Latest Eurostat data on international trade|last=|first=|date=14 February 2020|website=[[Eurostat]]|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=5 March 2019}}</ref>\n\n== Chronology==\n[[File:EU slide timeline post-Brexit partnership negotiations.png|thumb|450px|EU slides detailing timeline for post-Brexit EU\u2013UK partnership negotiations]]\nIn February 2020, the UK government published the UK\u2019s approach to the negotiations in a document presented by the prime minister to Parliament titled ''The Future Relationship with the EU-The UK\u2019s Approach to Negotiations''.<ref>{{cite web|title=The Future Relationship with the EU| publisher= [[Government of the United Kingdom]] |date= February 2020 | url=https://assets.publishing.service.gov.uk/government/uploads/system/uploads/attachment_data/file/868874/The_Future_Relationship_with_the_EU.pdf}}</ref>\n\nThe draft EU negotiating position was published on 3 February.<ref>{{Cite web |work=[[China Daily]] | author = Chen Weihua | date= 1 February 2020  |url=http://global.chinadaily.com.cn/a/202002/01/WS5e34e60ca310128217273f7d.html |title=Emotional send-off to give way to unsentimental talks}}</ref>\n\nThe UK expects to have a Canada style agreement, while the EU considers proximity and the size of its trade makes Canada style trade deal dependent on UK adoption of \"level playing field\" measures..<ref name=graun230220>{{Cite web|url=https://www.theguardian.com/politics/2020/feb/23/boris-johnson-european-union-trade-deal-brussels-talks|title=UK and Brussels clash over post-Brexit trade deal even before key talks begin|first=Michael|last=Savage|date=February 23, 2020|work = [[The Guardian]]}}</ref>\n\nEuropean mandate was published on 25 February 2020, while UK's mandate was published on 27 February 2020.<ref name=Euractiv250220>{{Cite web|url=https://www.euractiv.com/section/uk-europe/news/brexit-deal-will-be-difficult-barnier-says-as-ministers-agree-mandate/|title=Brexit deal will be 'difficult', Barnier says as ministers agree mandate|first=Benjamin|last=Fox|date=February 25, 2020}}</ref>\n\nTen rounds are planned every three weeks, alternately in Brussels and in London.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.theguardian.com/politics/2020/mar/02/eu-warns-uk-to-tone-down-political-rhetoric-as-trade-talks-start-brexit|title=EU warns UK to tone down political rhetoric as trade talks start|first=Lisa O'Carroll Brexit|last=correspondent|date=March 2, 2020|work = The Guardian}}</ref>\n\n===March 2020 negotiations===\nThe first official meeting was scheduled for the afternoon of the Monday 2 March 2020.<ref name=graun200301>{{Cite web|url=https://www.theguardian.com/politics/2020/mar/01/brexit-what-are-the-key-flashpoints-as-eu-uk-trade-talks-begin|title=Brexit: what are the key flashpoints as EU-UK trade talks begin?|first1=Daniel|last1=Boffey|first2=Jennifer|last2=Rankin|date=1 March 2020|work = The Guardian}}</ref> [[The Guardian]] anticipated that the 'flash-points' would be \"the level playing field' (on workers' rights, environmental protection, product safety standards and state aid), fisheries, dispute resolution, financial services, security and law enforcement, foreign policy and defence, cross-border transport, science and research\".<ref name=graun200301 /> In addition, the EU expressed its concern that the UK had not begun any work to implement the [[Brexit and the Irish border#2019 renegotiation: New Protocol|Ireland Protocol]] in the [[Withdrawal Agreement]] (a formal treaty) and that UK Government appeared to be backsliding on the obligations it had entered into.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.bbc.com/news/uk-northern-ireland-51632340 | title = Brexit: EU warns UK over goods checks between NI and GB | author = John Campbell | work= [[BBC News]] | date =25 February 2020 | accessdate= 10 March 2020}}</ref>\n\nIt was expected that the first rounds deals with regulatory standards and fisheries <ref name=Euractiv250220/><ref name=\"france24\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.france24.com/en/20200227-uk-threatens-to-walk-away-from-eu-trade-talks-if-no-progress-within-four-months|title=UK threatens to walk away from EU trade talks \u2018if no progress within four months\u2019|date=February 27, 2020|website=France 24}}</ref> It is understood that if those points are not agreed by the end of June, both sides will break off negotiations to concentrate on [[no-deal Brexit|no deal preparedness]].<ref name=\"france24\" />  \n\nThe first round of talks concluded on 5 March 2020.<ref name=graun050320>{{Cite web|url=https://www.theguardian.com/politics/2020/mar/05/barnier-warns-of-grave-differences-between-eu-and-uk-in-trade-talks|title=Barnier warns of grave differences between EU and UK in trade talks|author1=Daniel Boffey|author2=Jennifer Rankin|date=5 March 2020|work = [[The Guardian]]}}</ref> M. Barnier reported 'grave differences' between the sides, citing in particular the UK's reluctance to commit formally to continued participation in the (non-EU) [[European Convention on Human Rights]] as a serious obstacle to security and criminal intelligence cooperation.<ref name=graun050320 />\n\nThe second round, due to  take place in mid-March, was postponed due to the [[2020 coronavirus pandemic in Europe]]<!--Article includes the UK. For the purpose of this article, we don't need to dig deeper into the experiences of each country -->.<ref name=graun120320>{{cite news|url = https://www.theguardian.com/politics/2020/mar/12/uk-and-eu-agree-to-dial-down-rhetoric-in-brexit-talks | title=UK and EU agree to 'dial down rhetoric' in Brexit talks. Both sides expected to produce legal texts of negotiating positions next week | newspaper= The Guardian | author = Lisa O'Carroll |date= 12 March 2020| accessdate= 13 March 2020}}</ref> Both sides have been exploring alternative ways to continue discussions, including if possible the use of video conferences.<ref name=graun130320 /> On 13 March 2020, the draft of the Commission's proposals were circulated to national governments for comment.<ref name=graun130320>{{cite news|url = https://www.theguardian.com/politics/2020/mar/13/brexit-eu-demands-uk-negotiations-draft-treaty | title=Brexit: EU's demands in negotiations with UK revealed in draft treaty. Document highlights distance between two sides on issues including state aid rules | newspaper= The Guardian | author = Daniel Boffey  |date= 13 March 2020| accessdate= 13 March 2020}}</ref>\n\nIn late March, it emerged that negotiations had been abandoned as a result of the coronavirus pandemic, that negotiating via video-conferencing had not proved practicable, and that the British side had failed to table a legal draft that the sides could work on.<ref>{{cite news | newspaper = The Guardian | url= https://www.theguardian.com/world/2020/mar/26/covid-19-puts-post-brexit-relationship-talks-in-deep-freeze | title = UK-EU talks on post-Brexit relations 'in deep freeze' : Brussels laments London\u2019s failure to table comprehensive legal text to work on | author = Daniel Boffey | date= 26 March 2020 | accessdate= 26 March 2020 }}</ref> At the end of March, the UK side declared that it had shared its text, while concerns grew about the realism of a timetable set before the pandemic.<ref>{{cite news|url= https://www.ft.com/content/5c0bc7b2-8697-4493-8aa3-5766de1962b1 | title= Brexit: lost in transition | newspaper = Financial Times | date = 1 April 2020 | accessdate = 1 April 2020 | author= Jim Brunsden}}</ref> It also emerged that the UK had rejected an EU request for a permanent technical office in Belfast, saying that the request would go \"beyond what is stipulated in the withdrawal agreement\".<ref name=graun020420>{{cite news |url= https://www.theguardian.com/politics/2020/apr/02/uk-government-in-row-with-eu-over-proposed-office-in-belfast-brexit | title= UK government in row with EU over proposed office in Belfast: UK rejected initial request from Brussels during negotiations on post-Brexit Irish border controls | newspaper= The Guardian | author = Daniel Boffey | date= 2 April 2020 | accessdate= 3 April 2020}}</ref> \n(Article 12 of the Ireland Protocol states that the UK government is \u201cresponsible for implementing and applying the provisions of [EU] law\u201d but EU officials \u201cshall have the right to be present during any activities\u201d relating to checks and controls).<ref name=graun020420 />\n\n===April 2020 negotiations===\nIn April, against a background of the UK's and member states' preoccupation with managing the rapidly escalating coronvirus emergency,<ref>{{cite news| work = The Guardian | url= https://www.theguardian.com/politics/2020/apr/08/brexit-uk-plan-to-secure-trade-deal-by-december-is-fantasy-says-eu | title= Brexit: UK plan to agree trade deal by December is fantasy, says EU. Leaked letter reveals scale of bloc\u2019s inability to function during coronavirus outbreak | date= 8 April 2020 | accessdate=15 April 2020 | author = Daniel Boffey}}</ref> commentators began increasingly to question the practicality of the UK's timetable. Amanda Sloat, a senior fellow at [[Brookings Institution]] remarked \"In all circumstances it\u2019s very difficult to imagine how some sort of large scale trade deal between the U.K. and the EU gets done by the end of the year.\"<ref>{{cite news| work=CNBC | url= https://www.cnbc.com/2020/04/07/brexit-trade-deal-gets-tougher-as-coronavirus-strikes-officials-on-both-sides.html | title = Brexit trade deal gets tougher as coronavirus strikes officials on both sides | date= 7 April 2020 | accessdate=15 April 2020 | author = Weizhen Tan | quote=\"In all circumstances it\u2019s very difficult to imagine how some sort of large scale trade deal between the U.K. and the EU gets done by the end of the year,\" said Amanda Sloat, a senior fellow at [[Brookings Institution]].}}</ref> Preliminary negotiations resumed on 15 April, but appear to have been limited to agreeing the phasing of subsequent negotiations to end in June 2020.<ref>{{cite press release|publisher= Government of the United Kingdom | url=https://www.gov.uk/government/news/joint-statement-by-uk-and-eu-negotiators-following-the-videoconference-on-15-april-2020 | date = 15 April 2020 | accessdate = 19 April 2020 | title=Joint statement by UK and EU negotiators following the videoconference on 15 April 2020.}}</ref> (The deadline for completing negotiations is 30 June 2020).<ref name=IT-200420 /> The following day, the UK's lead negotiator reiterated his Government's position that the end date will not be changed:\n{{quote|text=As we prepare for the next Rounds of negotiations, I want to reiterate the Government's position on the transition period created following our withdrawal from the EU.  Transition ends on 31 December this year. We will not ask to extend it. If the EU asks we will say no. Extending would simply prolong negotiations, create even more uncertainty, leave us liable to pay more to the EU in future, and keep us bound by evolving EU laws at a time when we need to control our own affairs. In short, it is not in the UK's interest to extend.| author= [[David Frost (British diplomat)|David Frost]]<ref name=IT-200420>{{cite news|url=https://www.irishtimes.com/business/economy/britain-rules-out-extension-to-clinch-post-brexit-deal-1.4230648 |title =Britain rules out extension to clinch post-Brexit deal |author = Naomi O\u2019Leary |date= 16 April 2020|accessdate=April 20, 2020|work = [[Irish Times]]}}</ref> }}\n\nFull negotiations are began on 20 April, by video-conference. The issues to be addressed include the future trade relationship, security policy, trade rules and the contentious issue of fishing rights.<ref>{{cite news|work = The Week | url= https://www.theweek.co.uk/brexit/106638/brexit-the-state-of-affairs-as-negotiations-restart | title= Brexit: the state of affairs as negotiations restart: Virtual negotiations will begin next week, but time is running out to agree a deal | author = William Gritten | date=Apr 16, 2020 | accessdate = 19 April 2020 | quote=On the table are the crucial issues of the future trade relationship, including security policy, trade rules and the contentious issue of fishing rights. Westminster has yet to produce any proposals on the politically charged issue of access for EU boats to UK waters - and it could yet prove an intractable issue. }}</ref>\n\n==Negotiator teams==\n<!-- Picture of David Frost (British diplomat) needed. Please do not use picture of David Frost (d, 2013)! -->\n[[File:Barnier, Michel-9568.jpg|thumb|right|Michel Barnier]]\n\nThe two sides in the negotiations are the United Kingdom of Great Britain, and the European Union.\n\nFor the UK, prime minister Boris Johnson has chosen career diplomat [[David Frost (British diplomat)|David Frost]] as lead negotiator.\n\nOn the EU side, the main negotiator is [[Michel Barnier]],<ref name=graun200301/> who received his negotiating mandate from the [[European Council]] on 25 February 2020.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://ec.europa.eu/commission/presscorner/detail/en/ip_20_324 | title = Future EU-UK Partnership: European Commission receives mandate to begin negotiations with the UK (press release) | publisher = European Commission | date = 25 February 2020 | accessdate= 10 March 2020}}</ref>\n\n===EU Scope of the negotiation===\n\nThe EU has assumed that the UK will ask concessions for [[financial services]] while the EU would ask concessions on fisheries<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.theguardian.com/politics/2020/jan/13/city-access-eu-markets-eu-fleets-uk-fishing-rights-brexit|title=EU trade chief foresees 'financial services for fishing' Brexit bargain|first=Daniel|last=Boffey|date=January 13, 2020|work = The Guardian}}</ref>.\n\nOn the EU side, the scope of the negotiations could include:\n* Energy\n* Fisheries\n* Financial services: equivalence and cooperation<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://ec.europa.eu/info/european-union-and-united-kingdom-forging-new-partnership/future-partnership/guide-negotiations_en|title=Guide to the negotiations|website=[[European Commission]]}}</ref>\n* Foreign policy, defense and security\n* Free trade agreement\n* Governance\n* Law enforcement and judicial cooperation in criminal matters\n* Level playing field, sustainability\n* Mobility of persons\n* Partnership legal nature and architecture\n* Personal data protection (adequacy decisions)\n* Transport\n* UK participation in European Union programs\n\n==Main topics==\n=== Regulatory alignment===\n\nUK and EU agree on their aim for a free-trade agreement without any restriction on imports or exports, knows as zero tariffs, zero quotas<ref name=graun200301/>.\n\nDuring the talks preceding Brexit, some British government ministers said UK would seek to diverge from EU rules and standards. This was confirmed by Boris Johnson, just after Brexit.<ref name=Euronews200211/>\n\nThe issue of regulatory alignment is that the EU believes that the UK would need to 'closely shadow' EU regulations (on product safety, environmental protection, workers' rights, subsidies, etc.) to permit 'unfettered' trade in goods and services, while the UK declares that it will not do so.<ref name=\"france24\" />  The [[Withdrawal Agreement]] recognises that standards in [[Great Britain]] will diverge in many respects from those in the EU (with consequent loss of trade privileges in these areas), with [[Brexit and the Irish border#2019 renegotiation: New Protocol|a special status]] being accorded to Northern Ireland to keep open the [[Irish border]]. \n\n{{quote|\u201cWe aren\u2019t frightened by suggestions there is going to be friction, there are going to be greater barriers. We know that and have factored this in and we look further forward \u2013 to the gains of the future,\u201d|source=UK\u2019s chief negotiator, David Frost<ref name=euronews200226>{{Cite web|url=https://www.euronews.com/2020/02/26/what-are-the-sticking-points-in-post-brexit-uk-eu-trade-deal-euronews-answers|title=What are the UK-EU sticking points over a post-Brexit trade deal?|first=Alasdair|last=Sandford|date=February 26, 2020|website=euronews}}</ref>}}\n\nOn its side, the European Union expects the UK to commit to a \"level playing field\" on various topics in order to offer \"robust\" guarantees to ensure fair competition and protection of the standards.<ref name=euronews200226 /> [[President of the European Commission]], [[Ursula von der Leyen]], observed that zero tariffs and quotas requires the UK to commit to 'zero dumping'.<ref name=euronews200226 />\n\n===Fisheries issue===\n[[File:Sorting Crabs Fionnphort.jpg|thumb|right|Fishermen sorting [[velvet crab]]s at [[Fionnphort]], [[Scotland]]|alt=Photo of crabs in large, open metal box surrounded by fishermen]]\nThe fishing sector in the UK has ({{As of|2018||df=|lc=y}}) 22,000 jobs related to fish processing, 6,036 UK-registered vessel, and 11,961 fishermen.<ref name=bgraun230220>{{Cite web |url=https://www.theguardian.com/business/2020/feb/23/brexit-deal-fishing-cornwall-devon-trade-talks-europe |title=What\u2019s the catch? British fishermen\u2019s hopes and fears for Brexit deal |last=Sherwood|first=Harriet|date=February 23, 2020|work=The Guardian|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref> In the British economy, the fishing sector has a value of [[Pound sterling|\u00a3]]784 million. In comparison, financial services have a value of \u00a3132 billion.<ref name=bgraun230220 /> Despite being a little proportion of the economy, fishery is of high importance to both the UK and coastal EU states nearby.<ref name=Lords78>{{Cite web|url=https://publications.parliament.uk/pa/ld201617/ldselect/ldeucom/78/78.pdf|title=Brexit: fisheries|last=|first=|date=17 December 2016|website=House of Lords \u2013 European Union Committee|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=6 March 2020}}</ref><ref name=Euronews020320>{{Cite news|last=Sandford|first=Alasdair|url=https://www.euronews.com/2020/02/26/what-are-the-sticking-points-in-post-brexit-uk-eu-trade-deal-euronews-answers|title=What are the sticking points in a post-Brexit UK-EU trade deal? {{!}} Euronews answers|date=2 March 2020|work=Euronews|access-date=5 March 2020|url-status=live}}</ref> In 2018, 75 % of all seafood caught in the UK was exported, most to the EU, while of the seafood consumed in the UK, two thirds are imported.<ref name=bgraun230220 />\n\nThe EU has a [[common fisheries policy]] (CPF), which allows EU fishers access to waters of every other EU member state, outside the first 12 nautical miles (22 km) from the coast.<ref name=bgraun230220 /> Following the end of the transition period, the UK will become a third party coastal state with, in accordance with the [[United Nations Convention on the Law of the Sea]], an '[[exclusive economic zone]]' of 200 nautical miles from the coast.<ref name=bgraun230220 /><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://researchbriefings.parliament.uk/ResearchBriefing/Summary/CBP-8396|title=Fisheries and Brexit|last=Ares|first=Elena|date=30 October 2019|website=House of Commons Library|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=5 March 2020}}</ref> Under CPF, catch quotas are allocated for species individually, and distribute among the member states, who in turn distribute them to fishers.<ref name=Lords78 /> Most UK quotas are concentrated on few companies, and over half of the quotas are controlled by foreign-owned companies. The UK does not have the fishing capacity to fully catch their allowed quotas.<ref name=bgraun230220 />\n\nThe EU has linked negotiations on fishing policy to trade talks, while the UK wishes to keep them apart.<ref name=Euronews020320 /> A point to be negotiated is the length of the agreement: the EU expects a permanent agreement, the UK expects a Norwegian like annual agreement to be in line with biology of fish, aspirations of fishermen, and fisheries science.<ref name=bgraun230220 />\n\nIn exchange for a right for European [[Fishing trawler|trawler]]s to fish in British waters, France proposes that Britain should have the right to sell its fish and seafood products on the European market.<ref name=bgraun230220 />\n\n===Dispute resolution and the European Court of Justice===\n\nThe European Union expects a comprehensive trade agreement that covers trade, transport, foreign policy and fishing.<ref name=graun200301/> Consequently, it believes, resolution of any dispute related to the interpretation of EU law could only be determined by the  [[European Court of Justice]]<ref name=graun200301/>.\n\nThe United Kingdom aims to obtain a 'comprehensive free trade agreement' (like the EU's [[Comprehensive Economic and Trade Agreement|CETA]] agreement with Canada) that does not include fishing, security, transport or energy. These matters, it believes, should be covered in a separate deal where 'appropriate governance arrangements', rather than European Court of Justice, would adjudicate.<ref name=graun200301/>\n\n===Financial services===\n[[File:London.bankofengland.arp.jpg|thumb|right|The [[Bank of England]], the [[central bank]] of the United Kingdom]]\nThe EU-Canada deal does not contain financial passporting.<ref name=\"politico-uk-may-not-like-\" />\n\nAlso, the \"[[Most favoured nation|most favored nation]]\" clause will make every privilege given to the UK would also have to be given to Canada.<ref name=\"politico-uk-may-not-like-\" />\n\nIt is assumed a deal containing financial services cannot be negotiated in less than two years.<ref name=\"politico-uk-may-not-like-\" />\n\nFinancial services makes 6.9% of [[Economy of the United Kingdom|UK 2018 GDP]].\nEU considers that it is alone allowed to establish the equivalence decision in the interest of the Union. UK expects to maintain access to European clients of financial services, by avoiding future equivalence withdrawal decisions by the mean of appropriate consultation and structured processes<ref name=graun200301/>.\n\n===Security and law enforcement===\n\nFor the security and law enforcement matters, UK and EU issues include the [[European Convention on Human Rights]], [[Europol]], [[Eurojust]], and the [[European arrest warrant]].<ref name=graun200301/>\n\n==Expected benefits==\n\nAccording to the UN Conference on Trade and Development, a trade agreement between the UK and the EU would help limit the drop of exports from UK to EU to 9%, while the expected decrease would be 14% in case of no deal.<ref name=Euractiv250220/>\n\n== References ==\n{{reflist}}\n\n[[Category:Brexit]]\n[[Category:Foreign relations of the United Kingdom|European Union]]\n[[Category:Proposed free trade agreements]]\n[[Category:United Kingdom and the European Union]]\n", "text_old": "{{short description|The negotiation of a post-Brexit partnership and trade deal between the UK and the EU}}\n[[File:United Kingdom European Union Locator.svg|thumb|right|United Kingdom (green) and European Union (27 member states) orange]]\nThe '''Trade deal negotiation between the UK and EU''' is a post-[[Brexit]] negotiation between the parties that aims to achieve a [[free trade agreement|trade agreement]], to make trade easier than it would be without a trade deal. Such a deal might cover (or eliminate) both  [[tariff]] and [[non-tariff barriers to trade]].\n\nDuring the [[Brexit negotiations in 2017]], the sides agreed that trade negotiation could only start after the UK's withdrawal, because such negotiations could not happen when the UK still has a veto right within the EU.<ref>{{Cite news |url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/news/2017/04/29/eu-brexit-guidelines-document-really-means/ |title=EU Brexit guidelines: What's in the document, and what it really means |last=Foster |first=Peter |date=29 April 2017|newspaper=The Daily Telegraph |access-date=14 May 2017}}</ref> For this and other reasons, a [[transition period]] after Brexit day was defined to allow those negotiations. The transition period started on the first February 2020, in accordance with the [[Brexit withdrawal agreement|withdrawal agreement]]. The first deadline is the 31 December 2020, a deadline which can be extended for two years.<ref name=Euronews200211>{{Cite web|url=https://www.euronews.com/2020/02/11/brexit-draft-deal-first-of-many-hurdles-to-a-smooth-exit|title=Post-Brexit Guide: Where are we now? *latest updates*|first=Alasdair|last=Sandford|date=February 11, 2020|website=euronews}}</ref>. The British government has declared that it will not apply for any such extension.<ref>{{cite news| url= https://www.reuters.com/article/uk-britain-eu-johnson-transition/uk-will-not-extend-brexit-transition-period-johnsons-spokesman-idUSKBN1Z5139 | title = UK will not extend Brexit transition period - Johnson's spokesman | date =6 January 2020 | work = [[Reuters]] | accessdate=8 March 2020}}</ref>\n\nDuring Brexit negotiation, the UK clarified the only kind of trade deal the UK is interested is in, if any, is a [[Comprehensive Economic and Trade Agreement|Canadian style trade deal]]<ref name=\"politico-uk-may-not-like-\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.politico.eu/article/brexit-trade-deal-will-contain-financial-services-but-uk-may-not-like-it/|title=Brexit trade deal will contain financial services, but UK may not like it|first=Pierre|last=Brian\u00e7on|date=January 11, 2018|website=POLITICO}}</ref>, as documented in a famous [[Michel Barnier]] slide<ref name=\"15-12-2017\">{{cite web|url=https://ec.europa.eu/commission/sites/beta-political/files/slide_presented_by_barnier_at_euco_15-12-2017.pdf | title = Slide presented by Michel Barnier, European Commission Chief Negotiator, to the Heads of State and Government at the European Council (Article 50) on 15 December 2017| date=15 December 2017 | access-date = 8 March 2020| work= [[European Commission]]}}</ref>.\n\nAccording to an (unnamed) French government adviser speaking to journalist Pierre Brian\u00e7on of [[Politico.eu]], the sides have different approaches of this trade deal negotiation: \n* \"The UK wants to preserve as much as it can from the current situation. Their viewpoint is they\u2019re in, and what\u2019s being discussed is simply stripping away some components of the edifice\".<ref name=\"politico-uk-may-not-like-\" /> \n* given that the UK is legally out of the Union, the EU considers that each part of the relation has to be fully renegotiated bottom-up.<ref name=\"politico-uk-may-not-like-\" />\n\nUK needs a trade deal, because the UK is to be out of the [[European Single Market]] and [[European Union Customs Union]] as soon as the 1 January 2021.<ref name=bbc020320>{{Cite web|url=https://www.bbc.com/news/uk-47213842|title=Which countries does the UK do the most trade with?|first=Tom|last=Edgington|date=March 2, 2020|work=BBC News}}</ref> The trade deal would affect EU-UK trade, which accounts for 49% of international UK trade.<ref name=bbc020320 /> A Canadian style trade deal would offer the UK reduction on most of custom tariffs between the EU and UK, but without eliminating VAT, customs and [[phytosanitary]] checks.<ref name=bbc020320 /> The arrangements for its dominant [[financial services]] sector are of particular importance to the UK.<ref name=\"politico-uk-may-not-like-\" /> \n\n==EU-UK trade before Brexit==\n\nThe EU is the [[List of the largest trading partners of United Kingdom|UK's largest trading partner]], and in 2018 the bloc made up 45% of UK exports and 53% of UK imports.<ref name=lords7851 /> Outside EU, the biggest trading partner of the UK is USA, which in 2018 made up 19% of UK exports and 11% of UK imports.<ref name=lords7851>{{Cite web|url=https://researchbriefings.files.parliament.uk/documents/CBP-7851/CBP-7851.pdf|title=Statistics on UK-EU trade|last=Ward|first=Matthew|date=16 December 2019|website=House of Commons Library|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=5 March 2019}}</ref>\n\nFor the EU27, the UK is its second largest export market (after USA), and third largest import market (after China and USA).<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://trade.ec.europa.eu/doclib/docs/2013/december/tradoc_151969.pdf|title=Latest Eurostat data on international trade|last=|first=|date=14 February 2020|website=[[Eurostat]]|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=5 March 2019}}</ref>\n\n== Chronology==\n[[File:EU slide timeline post-Brexit partnership negotiations.png|thumb|450px|EU slides detailing timeline for post-Brexit EU\u2013UK partnership negotiations]]\nIn February 2020, the UK government published the UK\u2019s approach to the negotiations in a document presented by the prime minister to Parliament titled ''The Future Relationship with the EU-The UK\u2019s Approach to Negotiations''.<ref>{{cite web|title=The Future Relationship with the EU| publisher= [[Government of the United Kingdom]] |date= February 2020 | url=https://assets.publishing.service.gov.uk/government/uploads/system/uploads/attachment_data/file/868874/The_Future_Relationship_with_the_EU.pdf}}</ref>\n\nThe draft EU negotiating position was published on 3 February.<ref>{{Cite web |work=[[China Daily]] | author = Chen Weihua | date= 1 February 2020  |url=http://global.chinadaily.com.cn/a/202002/01/WS5e34e60ca310128217273f7d.html |title=Emotional send-off to give way to unsentimental talks}}</ref>\n\nThe UK expects to have a Canada style agreement, while the EU considers proximity and the size of its trade makes Canada style trade deal dependent on UK adoption of \"level playing field\" measures..<ref name=graun230220>{{Cite web|url=https://www.theguardian.com/politics/2020/feb/23/boris-johnson-european-union-trade-deal-brussels-talks|title=UK and Brussels clash over post-Brexit trade deal even before key talks begin|first=Michael|last=Savage|date=February 23, 2020|work = [[The Guardian]]}}</ref>\n\nEuropean mandate was published on 25 February 2020, while UK's mandate was published on 27 February 2020.<ref name=Euractiv250220>{{Cite web|url=https://www.euractiv.com/section/uk-europe/news/brexit-deal-will-be-difficult-barnier-says-as-ministers-agree-mandate/|title=Brexit deal will be 'difficult', Barnier says as ministers agree mandate|first=Benjamin|last=Fox|date=February 25, 2020}}</ref>\n\nTen rounds are planned every three weeks, alternately in Brussels and in London.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.theguardian.com/politics/2020/mar/02/eu-warns-uk-to-tone-down-political-rhetoric-as-trade-talks-start-brexit|title=EU warns UK to tone down political rhetoric as trade talks start|first=Lisa O'Carroll Brexit|last=correspondent|date=March 2, 2020|work = The Guardian}}</ref>\n\n===March 2020 negotiations===\nThe first official meeting was scheduled for the afternoon of the Monday 2 March 2020.<ref name=graun200301>{{Cite web|url=https://www.theguardian.com/politics/2020/mar/01/brexit-what-are-the-key-flashpoints-as-eu-uk-trade-talks-begin|title=Brexit: what are the key flashpoints as EU-UK trade talks begin?|first1=Daniel|last1=Boffey|first2=Jennifer|last2=Rankin|date=1 March 2020|work = The Guardian}}</ref> [[The Guardian]] anticipated that the 'flash-points' would be \"the level playing field' (on workers' rights, environmental protection, product safety standards and state aid), fisheries, dispute resolution, financial services, security and law enforcement, foreign policy and defence, cross-border transport, science and research\".<ref name=graun200301 /> In addition, the EU expressed its concern that the UK had not begun any work to implement the [[Brexit and the Irish border#2019 renegotiation: New Protocol|Ireland Protocol]] in the [[Withdrawal Agreement]] (a formal treaty) and that UK Government appeared to be backsliding on the obligations it had entered into.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.bbc.com/news/uk-northern-ireland-51632340 | title = Brexit: EU warns UK over goods checks between NI and GB | author = John Campbell | work= [[BBC News]] | date =25 February 2020 | accessdate= 10 March 2020}}</ref>\n\nIt was expected that the first rounds deals with regulatory standards and fisheries <ref name=Euractiv250220/><ref name=\"france24\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.france24.com/en/20200227-uk-threatens-to-walk-away-from-eu-trade-talks-if-no-progress-within-four-months|title=UK threatens to walk away from EU trade talks \u2018if no progress within four months\u2019|date=February 27, 2020|website=France 24}}</ref> It is understood that if those points are not agreed by the end of June, both sides will break off negotiations to concentrate on [[no-deal Brexit|no deal preparedness]].<ref name=\"france24\" />  \n\nThe first round of talks concluded on 5 March 2020.<ref name=graun050320>{{Cite web|url=https://www.theguardian.com/politics/2020/mar/05/barnier-warns-of-grave-differences-between-eu-and-uk-in-trade-talks|title=Barnier warns of grave differences between EU and UK in trade talks|author1=Daniel Boffey|author2=Jennifer Rankin|date=5 March 2020|work = [[The Guardian]]}}</ref> M. Barnier reported 'grave differences' between the sides, citing in particular the UK's reluctance to commit formally to continued participation in the (non-EU) [[European Convention on Human Rights]] as a serious obstacle to security and criminal intelligence cooperation.<ref name=graun050320 />\n\nThe second round, due to  take place in mid-March, was postponed due to the [[2020 coronavirus pandemic in Europe]]<!--Article includes the UK. For the purpose of this article, we don't need to dig deeper into the experiences of each country -->.<ref name=graun120320>{{cite news|url = https://www.theguardian.com/politics/2020/mar/12/uk-and-eu-agree-to-dial-down-rhetoric-in-brexit-talks | title=UK and EU agree to 'dial down rhetoric' in Brexit talks. Both sides expected to produce legal texts of negotiating positions next week | newspaper= The Guardian | author = Lisa O'Carroll |date= 12 March 2020| accessdate= 13 March 2020}}</ref> Both sides have been exploring alternative ways to continue discussions, including if possible the use of video conferences.<ref name=graun130320 /> On 13 March 2020, the draft of the Commission's proposals were circulated to national governments for comment.<ref name=graun130320>{{cite news|url = https://www.theguardian.com/politics/2020/mar/13/brexit-eu-demands-uk-negotiations-draft-treaty | title=Brexit: EU's demands in negotiations with UK revealed in draft treaty. Document highlights distance between two sides on issues including state aid rules | newspaper= The Guardian | author = Daniel Boffey  |date= 13 March 2020| accessdate= 13 March 2020}}</ref>\n\nIn late March, it emerged that negotiations had been abandoned as a result of the coronavirus pandemic, that negotiating via video-conferencing had not proved practicable, and that the British side had failed to table a legal draft that the sides could work on.<ref>{{cite news | newspaper = The Guardian | url= https://www.theguardian.com/world/2020/mar/26/covid-19-puts-post-brexit-relationship-talks-in-deep-freeze | title = UK-EU talks on post-Brexit relations 'in deep freeze' : Brussels laments London\u2019s failure to table comprehensive legal text to work on | author = Daniel Boffey | date= 26 March 2020 | accessdate= 26 March 2020 }}</ref> At the end of March, the UK side declared that it had shared its text, while concerns grew about the realism of a timetable set before the pandemic.<ref>{{cite news|url= https://www.ft.com/content/5c0bc7b2-8697-4493-8aa3-5766de1962b1 | title= Brexit: lost in transition | newspaper = Financial Times | date = 1 April 2020 | accessdate = 1 April 2020 | author= Jim Brunsden}}</ref> It also emerged that the UK had rejected an EU request for a permanent technical office in Belfast, saying that the request would go \"beyond what is stipulated in the withdrawal agreement\".<ref name=graun020420>{{cite news |url= https://www.theguardian.com/politics/2020/apr/02/uk-government-in-row-with-eu-over-proposed-office-in-belfast-brexit | title= UK government in row with EU over proposed office in Belfast: UK rejected initial request from Brussels during negotiations on post-Brexit Irish border controls | newspaper= The Guardian | author = Daniel Boffey | date= 2 April 2020 | accessdate= 3 April 2020}}</ref> \n(Article 12 of the Ireland Protocol states that the UK government is \u201cresponsible for implementing and applying the provisions of [EU] law\u201d but EU officials \u201cshall have the right to be present during any activities\u201d relating to checks and controls).<ref name=graun020420 />\n\n===April 2020 negotiations===\nIn April, against a background of the UK's and member states' preoccupation with managing the rapidly escalating coronvirus emergency,<ref>{{cite news| work = The Guardian | url= https://www.theguardian.com/politics/2020/apr/08/brexit-uk-plan-to-secure-trade-deal-by-december-is-fantasy-says-eu | title= Brexit: UK plan to agree trade deal by December is fantasy, says EU. Leaked letter reveals scale of bloc\u2019s inability to function during coronavirus outbreak | date= 8 April 2020 | accessdate=15 April 2020 | author = Daniel Boffey}}</ref> commentators began increasingly to question the practicality of the UK's timetable. Amanda Sloat, a senior fellow at [[Brookings Institution]] remarked \"In all circumstances it\u2019s very difficult to imagine how some sort of large scale trade deal between the U.K. and the EU gets done by the end of the year.\"<ref>{{cite news| work=CNBC | url= https://www.cnbc.com/2020/04/07/brexit-trade-deal-gets-tougher-as-coronavirus-strikes-officials-on-both-sides.html | title = Brexit trade deal gets tougher as coronavirus strikes officials on both sides | date= 7 April 2020 | accessdate=15 April 2020 | author = Weizhen Tan | quote=\"In all circumstances it\u2019s very difficult to imagine how some sort of large scale trade deal between the U.K. and the EU gets done by the end of the year,\" said Amanda Sloat, a senior fellow at [[Brookings Institution]].}}</ref> Preliminary negotiations resumed on 15 April, but appear to have been limited to agreeing the phasing of subsequent negotiations to end in June 2020.<ref>{{cite press release|publisher= Government of the United Kingdom | url=https://www.gov.uk/government/news/joint-statement-by-uk-and-eu-negotiators-following-the-videoconference-on-15-april-2020 | date = 15 April 2020 | accessdate = 19 April 2020 | title=Joint statement by UK and EU negotiators following the videoconference on 15 April 2020.}}</ref> (The deadline for completing negotiations is 30 June 2020).<ref name=IT-200420 /> The following day, the UK's lead negotiator reiterated his Government's position that the end date will not be changed:\n{{quote|text=As we prepare for the next Rounds of negotiations, I want to reiterate the Government's position on the transition period created following our withdrawal from the EU.  Transition ends on 31 December this year. We will not ask to extend it. If the EU asks we will say no. Extending would simply prolong negotiations, create even more uncertainty, leave us liable to pay more to the EU in future, and keep us bound by evolving EU laws at a time when we need to control our own affairs. In short, it is not in the UK's interest to extend.| author= [[David Frost (British diplomat)|David Frost]]<ref name=IT-200420>{{cite news|url=https://www.irishtimes.com/business/economy/britain-rules-out-extension-to-clinch-post-brexit-deal-1.4230648 |title =Britain rules out extension to clinch post-Brexit deal |author = Naomi O\u2019Leary |date= 16 April 2020|accessdate=April 20, 2020|work = [[Irish Times]]}}</ref> }}\n\nFull negotiations are scheduled to begin on 20 April, by video-conference. The issues to be addressed include the future trade relationship, security policy, trade rules and the contentious issue of fishing rights.<ref>{{cite news|work = The Week | url= https://www.theweek.co.uk/brexit/106638/brexit-the-state-of-affairs-as-negotiations-restart | title= Brexit: the state of affairs as negotiations restart: Virtual negotiations will begin next week, but time is running out to agree a deal | author = William Gritten | date=Apr 16, 2020 | accessdate = 19 April 2020 | quote=On the table are the crucial issues of the future trade relationship, including security policy, trade rules and the contentious issue of fishing rights. Westminster has yet to produce any proposals on the politically charged issue of access for EU boats to UK waters - and it could yet prove an intractable issue. }}</ref>\n\n==Negotiator teams==\n<!-- Picture of David Frost (British diplomat) needed. Please do not use picture of David Frost (d, 2013)! -->\n[[File:Barnier, Michel-9568.jpg|thumb|right|Michel Barnier]]\n\nThe two sides in the negotiations are the United Kingdom of Great Britain, and the European Union.\n\nFor the UK, prime minister Boris Johnson has chosen career diplomat [[David Frost (British diplomat)|David Frost]] as lead negotiator.\n\nOn the EU side, the main negotiator is [[Michel Barnier]],<ref name=graun200301/> who received his negotiating mandate from the [[European Council]] on 25 February 2020.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://ec.europa.eu/commission/presscorner/detail/en/ip_20_324 | title = Future EU-UK Partnership: European Commission receives mandate to begin negotiations with the UK (press release) | publisher = European Commission | date = 25 February 2020 | accessdate= 10 March 2020}}</ref>\n\n===EU Scope of the negotiation===\n\nThe EU has assumed that the UK will ask concessions for [[financial services]] while the EU would ask concessions on fisheries<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.theguardian.com/politics/2020/jan/13/city-access-eu-markets-eu-fleets-uk-fishing-rights-brexit|title=EU trade chief foresees 'financial services for fishing' Brexit bargain|first=Daniel|last=Boffey|date=January 13, 2020|work = The Guardian}}</ref>.\n\nOn the EU side, the scope of the negotiations could include:\n* Energy\n* Fisheries\n* Financial services: equivalence and cooperation<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://ec.europa.eu/info/european-union-and-united-kingdom-forging-new-partnership/future-partnership/guide-negotiations_en|title=Guide to the negotiations|website=[[European Commission]]}}</ref>\n* Foreign policy, defense and security\n* Free trade agreement\n* Governance\n* Law enforcement and judicial cooperation in criminal matters\n* Level playing field, sustainability\n* Mobility of persons\n* Partnership legal nature and architecture\n* Personal data protection (adequacy decisions)\n* Transport\n* UK participation in European Union programs\n\n==Main topics==\n=== Regulatory alignment===\n\nUK and EU agree on their aim for a free-trade agreement without any restriction on imports or exports, knows as zero tariffs, zero quotas<ref name=graun200301/>.\n\nDuring the talks preceding Brexit, some British government ministers said UK would seek to diverge from EU rules and standards. This was confirmed by Boris Johnson, just after Brexit.<ref name=Euronews200211/>\n\nThe issue of regulatory alignment is that the EU believes that the UK would need to 'closely shadow' EU regulations (on product safety, environmental protection, workers' rights, subsidies, etc.) to permit 'unfettered' trade in goods and services, while the UK declares that it will not do so.<ref name=\"france24\" />  The [[Withdrawal Agreement]] recognises that standards in [[Great Britain]] will diverge in many respects from those in the EU (with consequent loss of trade privileges in these areas), with [[Brexit and the Irish border#2019 renegotiation: New Protocol|a special status]] being accorded to Northern Ireland to keep open the [[Irish border]]. \n\n{{quote|\u201cWe aren\u2019t frightened by suggestions there is going to be friction, there are going to be greater barriers. We know that and have factored this in and we look further forward \u2013 to the gains of the future,\u201d|source=UK\u2019s chief negotiator, David Frost<ref name=euronews200226>{{Cite web|url=https://www.euronews.com/2020/02/26/what-are-the-sticking-points-in-post-brexit-uk-eu-trade-deal-euronews-answers|title=What are the UK-EU sticking points over a post-Brexit trade deal?|first=Alasdair|last=Sandford|date=February 26, 2020|website=euronews}}</ref>}}\n\nOn its side, the European Union expects the UK to commit to a \"level playing field\" on various topics in order to offer \"robust\" guarantees to ensure fair competition and protection of the standards.<ref name=euronews200226 /> [[President of the European Commission]], [[Ursula von der Leyen]], observed that zero tariffs and quotas requires the UK to commit to 'zero dumping'.<ref name=euronews200226 />\n\n===Fisheries issue===\n[[File:Sorting Crabs Fionnphort.jpg|thumb|right|Fishermen sorting [[velvet crab]]s at [[Fionnphort]], [[Scotland]]|alt=Photo of crabs in large, open metal box surrounded by fishermen]]\nThe fishing sector in the UK has ({{As of|2018||df=|lc=y}}) 22,000 jobs related to fish processing, 6,036 UK-registered vessel, and 11,961 fishermen.<ref name=bgraun230220>{{Cite web |url=https://www.theguardian.com/business/2020/feb/23/brexit-deal-fishing-cornwall-devon-trade-talks-europe |title=What\u2019s the catch? British fishermen\u2019s hopes and fears for Brexit deal |last=Sherwood|first=Harriet|date=February 23, 2020|work=The Guardian|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref> In the British economy, the fishing sector has a value of [[Pound sterling|\u00a3]]784 million. In comparison, financial services have a value of \u00a3132 billion.<ref name=bgraun230220 /> Despite being a little proportion of the economy, fishery is of high importance to both the UK and coastal EU states nearby.<ref name=Lords78>{{Cite web|url=https://publications.parliament.uk/pa/ld201617/ldselect/ldeucom/78/78.pdf|title=Brexit: fisheries|last=|first=|date=17 December 2016|website=House of Lords \u2013 European Union Committee|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=6 March 2020}}</ref><ref name=Euronews020320>{{Cite news|last=Sandford|first=Alasdair|url=https://www.euronews.com/2020/02/26/what-are-the-sticking-points-in-post-brexit-uk-eu-trade-deal-euronews-answers|title=What are the sticking points in a post-Brexit UK-EU trade deal? {{!}} Euronews answers|date=2 March 2020|work=Euronews|access-date=5 March 2020|url-status=live}}</ref> In 2018, 75 % of all seafood caught in the UK was exported, most to the EU, while of the seafood consumed in the UK, two thirds are imported.<ref name=bgraun230220 />\n\nThe EU has a [[common fisheries policy]] (CPF), which allows EU fishers access to waters of every other EU member state, outside the first 12 nautical miles (22 km) from the coast.<ref name=bgraun230220 /> Following the end of the transition period, the UK will become a third party coastal state with, in accordance with the [[United Nations Convention on the Law of the Sea]], an '[[exclusive economic zone]]' of 200 nautical miles from the coast.<ref name=bgraun230220 /><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://researchbriefings.parliament.uk/ResearchBriefing/Summary/CBP-8396|title=Fisheries and Brexit|last=Ares|first=Elena|date=30 October 2019|website=House of Commons Library|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=5 March 2020}}</ref> Under CPF, catch quotas are allocated for species individually, and distribute among the member states, who in turn distribute them to fishers.<ref name=Lords78 /> Most UK quotas are concentrated on few companies, and over half of the quotas are controlled by foreign-owned companies. The UK does not have the fishing capacity to fully catch their allowed quotas.<ref name=bgraun230220 />\n\nThe EU has linked negotiations on fishing policy to trade talks, while the UK wishes to keep them apart.<ref name=Euronews020320 /> A point to be negotiated is the length of the agreement: the EU expects a permanent agreement, the UK expects a Norwegian like annual agreement to be in line with biology of fish, aspirations of fishermen, and fisheries science.<ref name=bgraun230220 />\n\nIn exchange for a right for European [[Fishing trawler|trawler]]s to fish in British waters, France proposes that Britain should have the right to sell its fish and seafood products on the European market.<ref name=bgraun230220 />\n\n===Dispute resolution and the European Court of Justice===\n\nThe European Union expects a comprehensive trade agreement that covers trade, transport, foreign policy and fishing.<ref name=graun200301/> Consequently, it believes, resolution of any dispute related to the interpretation of EU law could only be determined by the  [[European Court of Justice]]<ref name=graun200301/>.\n\nThe United Kingdom aims to obtain a 'comprehensive free trade agreement' (like the EU's [[Comprehensive Economic and Trade Agreement|CETA]] agreement with Canada) that does not include fishing, security, transport or energy. These matters, it believes, should be covered in a separate deal where 'appropriate governance arrangements', rather than European Court of Justice, would adjudicate.<ref name=graun200301/>\n\n===Financial services===\n[[File:London.bankofengland.arp.jpg|thumb|right|The [[Bank of England]], the [[central bank]] of the United Kingdom]]\nThe EU-Canada deal does not contain financial passporting.<ref name=\"politico-uk-may-not-like-\" />\n\nAlso, the \"[[Most favoured nation|most favored nation]]\" clause will make every privilege given to the UK would also have to be given to Canada.<ref name=\"politico-uk-may-not-like-\" />\n\nIt is assumed a deal containing financial services cannot be negotiated in less than two years.<ref name=\"politico-uk-may-not-like-\" />\n\nFinancial services makes 6.9% of [[Economy of the United Kingdom|UK 2018 GDP]].\nEU considers that it is alone allowed to establish the equivalence decision in the interest of the Union. UK expects to maintain access to European clients of financial services, by avoiding future equivalence withdrawal decisions by the mean of appropriate consultation and structured processes<ref name=graun200301/>.\n\n===Security and law enforcement===\n\nFor the security and law enforcement matters, UK and EU issues include the [[European Convention on Human Rights]], [[Europol]], [[Eurojust]], and the [[European arrest warrant]].<ref name=graun200301/>\n\n==Expected benefits==\n\nAccording to the UN Conference on Trade and Development, a trade agreement between the UK and the EU would help limit the drop of exports from UK to EU to 9%, while the expected decrease would be 14% in case of no deal.<ref name=Euractiv250220/>\n\n== References ==\n{{reflist}}\n\n[[Category:Brexit]]\n[[Category:Foreign relations of the United Kingdom|European Union]]\n[[Category:Proposed free trade agreements]]\n[[Category:United Kingdom and the European Union]]\n", "name_user": "John Maynard Friedman", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eApril 2020 negotiations:20 april was two days ago, I assume negotiations actually happened but comuniqu\u00e9 not expected", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Trade_deal_negotiation_between_the_UK_and_EU"}
{"title_page": "Aaron Taylor-Johnson", "text_new": "{{Short description|English actor}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=March 2020}}\n{{EngvarB|date=March 2020}}\n{{Infobox person\n| name               = Aaron Taylor-Johnson\n| image              = Aaron Taylor-Johnson SDCC 2014 (cropped).jpg\n| caption            = Johnson at the 2014 [[San Diego Comic Con]]\n| birth_name         = Aaron Perry Johnson\n| birth_date         = {{Birth date and age|df=y|1990|6|13}}\n| birth_place        = [[High Wycombe]], Buckinghamshire, England\n| nationality        = British\n| othername          = Aaron Johnson\n| occupation         = Actor, screenwriter\n| years_active       = 2000\u2013present\n| children           = 2\n| spouse             = {{marriage|[[Sam Taylor-Johnson|Sam Taylor-Wood]]|2012}}\n}}\n'''Aaron Perry Taylor-Johnson''' (n\u00e9 '''Johnson''';<ref name=birth>''Births, Marriages & Deaths Index of England & Wales, 1916\u20132005.''; at ancestry.com</ref> born 13 June 1990)<ref name=TimesOnline/><ref name=UKTVGuide/> is an English<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.standard.co.uk/lifestyle/esmagazine/aaron-taylor-johnson-i-was-raised-by-women-now-i-m-raising-women-and-sam-s-the-best-woman-i-know-9323936.html|title=Aaron Taylor-Johnson: 'I was raised by women. Now I\u2019m raising women. And Sam's the best woman I know'|work=London Evening Standard|date=8 May 2014|last=Rafanelli|first=Stephanie|accessdate=9 December 2019}}</ref> actor and screenwriter, best known for his portrayal of the [[Kick-Ass (character)|titular character]] in the ''[[Kick-Ass (film)|Kick-Ass]]'' films and [[Quicksilver (comics)|Quicksilver]] in ''[[Avengers: Age of Ultron]]'' (2015).  He is a widely considered by Harry Potter fans to be the perfect actor to play a young James Potter.\n\nTaylor-Johnson began performing at age six and has appeared in films such as ''[[Shanghai Knights]]'' (2003), playing a young [[Charlie Chaplin]], ''[[The Illusionist (2006 film)|The Illusionist]]'' (2006) and ''[[Angus, Thongs and Perfect Snogging]]'' (2008). He had his breakthrough performance in the [[John Lennon]] biopic ''[[Nowhere Boy]]'' (2009). He went on to portray Ben in the [[Oliver Stone]]-directed crime thriller ''[[Savages (2012 film)|Savages]]'' (2012), Russian aristocrat Count Vronsky in [[Joe Wright]]'s adaptation of ''[[Anna Karenina (2012 film)|Anna Karenina]]'' (2012) and Lt. Brody in [[Gareth Edwards (director)|Gareth Edwards]]' monster movie ''[[Godzilla (2014 film)|Godzilla]]'' (2014). For his performance as psychopathic drifter Ray Marcus in [[Tom Ford]]'s thriller ''[[Nocturnal Animals]]'' (2016), he won the [[Golden Globe Award for Best Supporting Actor \u2013 Motion Picture|Golden Globe Award for Best Supporting Actor]] and was nominated for the [[BAFTA Award for Best Actor in a Supporting Role]].  \n\n==Early life==\nAaron Perry Johnson was born in [[High Wycombe]], Buckinghamshire,<ref>{{cite news |url= https://www.nytimes.com/movies/person/893722/Aaron-Johnson/biography |title= Aaron Johnson biography |work= NYTimes.com Movies & TV |publisher= [[The New York Times]] ([[AllMovie|All Movie Guide]] and [[Baseline (database)|Baseline]]) |accessdate= 29 October 2011}}</ref> the son of Sarah and Robert Johnson, a [[housewife]] mother and civil engineer father, respectively.<ref name=UKTVGuide>{{cite web|url=http://uk-tv-guide.com/celebrity/Aaron+Johnson/103417|archive-url=https://archive.today/20130913180604/http://uk-tv-guide.com/celebrity/Aaron+Johnson/103417|url-status=dead|archive-date=13 September 2013|title=Aaron Johnson profile|publisher=Uk-tv-guide.com|accessdate=26 October 2011}}</ref><ref name=\"timesref02\">{{cite news|last=Maher|first=Kevin|title=Aaron Johnson: Beatle mania|newspaper=The Times|date=3 October 2009|url=http://entertainment.timesonline.co.uk/tol/arts_and_entertainment/film/london_film_festival/article6852334.ece?print=yes&randnum=1151003209000|accessdate=24 April 2010|location=London}}</ref> He has a sister, Gemma, who appeared in his film ''[[Tom & Thomas]]'' (2002) in a small role.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://myeveryzine.com/story/10-things-know-about-aaron-johnson/|title=10 Things to Know About Aaron Johnson|first=Grace|last=Gavilanes|date=8 July 2012}}</ref> He is [[British Jews|Jewish]].<ref>{{cite news | url=https://www.theguardian.com/film/2015/apr/23/aaron-taylor-johnson-avengers-age-ultron-interview | title=Aaron Taylor-Johnson: 'Changing my name felt beautiful' | newspaper=[[The Guardian]] | date=23 April 2015 | accessdate=9 August 2015 | author=Gilbey, Ryan|quote=He liked it recently when someone said he resembled a fashionable Hasidic Jew. \u201cThat was nice because I have really curly hair and also I\u2019m Jewish,\u201d he explains.}}</ref> He was educated at [[Holmer Green Senior School]]<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.hgss.co.uk/default.aspx?id=373|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20150404070713/http://www.hgss.co.uk/default.aspx?id=373|url-status=dead|title=Hgss.co.uk|archivedate=4 April 2015}}</ref> and attended the Jackie Palmer Stage School in High Wycombe between 1996 and 2008, where he studied drama, tap, jazz, acrobatics, and singing.<ref>{{cite news |first=Rebecca |last=Cain |title=Another successful year for the Jackie Palmer Stage School and agency|url=http://www.bucksfreepress.co.uk/news/4829177.Wycombe_s_stage_school_s_pupils_star_on_TV/ |newspaper=[[Bucks Free Press]] |date=3 January 2010 |accessdate=3 January 2010}}</ref>\n\n==Career==\nTaylor-Johnson began acting at the age of six. On stage, he appeared in a London production of [[Shakespeare]]'s ''[[Macbeth]]'', playing the son of [[Macduff (Macbeth)|Macduff]] alongside [[Rufus Sewell]], who played [[Macbeth]], in 1999.<ref>{{cite web |title=Sewell to Return to Stage in Macbeth |url=http://www.whatsonstage.com/news/theatre/london/E0607221502/Rufus+Sewell+to+Return+to+Stage+in+Macbeth.html |archivedate=12 April 2013 |archiveurl=https://archive.today/20130412044133/http://www.whatsonstage.com/news/theatre/london/E0607221502/Rufus+Sewell+to+Return+to+Stage+in+Macbeth.html |url-status=dead |access-date=16 February 2013 }}</ref> He appeared in [[Arthur Miller]]\u2019s ''[[All My Sons]]'' in 2000. His television roles have included Niker in the 2004 [[BBC]] adaptation of the novel ''[[Feather Boy]]'', Aaron in [[Danny Brocklehurst]]'s [[ITV1]] serial ''[[Talk to Me (UK TV series)|Talk to Me]]'', and Owen Stephens in ''[[Nearly Famous]]''.<ref name=TimesOnline>{{cite news|url=http://entertainment.timesonline.co.uk/tol/arts_and_entertainment/film/article6953190.ece|title=The Times: Entertainment|work=The Times|accessdate=26 October 2011|location=London|first=Sadie |last=Gray}}</ref> In 2003, Taylor-Johnson appeared as a young [[Charlie Chaplin]] in ''[[Shanghai Knights]]'', with Chaplin depicted as a member of a London gang of street thugs. In 2006, he appeared in ''[[The Illusionist (2006 film)|The Illusionist]]'', appearing in the early flashback scenes as [[Edward Norton]]'s character, Eduard Abramovicz, as a teenager. The scenes show the young Eduard as he first learns magic, and to do this, Johnson had to learn how to perform the ball trick displayed by his character. He learned how to perform the balancing of the egg on the stick, although that was effected mechanically.<ref>Writer/director [[Neil Burger]] explains this on the film's DVD commentary.</ref> Also in 2006, he starred in the film ''[[The Thief Lord (film)|The Thief Lord]]'', as Prosper.\n[[File:Aaron Taylor-Johnson by Gage Skidmore.jpg|thumb|left|150px|Johnson at the 2013 [[San Diego Comic-Con]] promoting ''[[Godzilla (2014 film)|Godzilla'']]'']]\nTaylor-Johnson appeared as [[John Lennon]] in the 2009 biographical film film ''[[Nowhere Boy]]'', directed by [[Sam Taylor-Wood]]. His performance saw him receive the [[Empire Award for Best Newcomer]] and he was also nominated for [[London Film Critics Circle Awards 2009#Young British Performer of the Year|Young British Performer of the Year]] by the [[London Film Critics' Circle]]. In 2010, Taylor-Johnson appeared as [[Kick-Ass (character)|David \"Dave\" Lizewski/Kick-Ass]], the lead character in ''[[Kick-Ass (film)|Kick-Ass]]'', based on the [[Kick-Ass (comic)|superhero comic book of the same name]] by Scottish writer [[Mark Millar]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.aintitcool.com/node/43367 |title=Ain't It Cool News: The best in movie, TV, DVD, and comic book news |publisher=Aintitcool.com|accessdate=26 October 2011}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|last=Gholson|first=John |url=http://www.scifisquad.com/2009/12/14/kick-ass-kicks-ass-at-bnat|title='Kick-Ass' Kicks Ass at BNAT \u2013 The Moviefone Blog|publisher=Scifisquad.com|date=2 May 2011|accessdate=26 October 2011}}</ref> His performance in ''Kick-Ass'' saw him nominated for the [[BAFTA Rising Star Award]]. He has also appeared as the central character, William, in [[Hideo Nakata]]'s ''[[Chatroom (film)|Chatroom]]''.<ref name=TimesOnline/> In December 2010, Taylor-Johnson joined the cast of ''[[Albert Nobbs]]'' as a replacement for [[Orlando Bloom]], who dropped out of the production due to his wife's pregnancy.<ref name=nobbs>{{cite web|last=Sneider|first=Jeff|url=http://www.thewrap.com/node/23054|title=Aaron Johnson Joins Mia Wasikowska in 'Albert Nobbs'|publisher=Thewrap.com|date=6 December 2010|accessdate=26 October 2011}}</ref> Taylor-Johnson starred in [[R.E.M.]]'s 2011 music video \"[[\u00dcberlin]]\", which was also directed by his then-fianc\u00e9e.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.theguardian.com/music/video/2011/mar/02/rem-uberlin|title=Watch REM's Uberlin, starring Aaron Johnson \u2013 video|newspaper=The Guardian|date=2 March 2011|accessdate=4 December 2011|location=London}}</ref>\n\nIn 2012, Taylor-Johnson played Count Vronsky in ''[[Anna Karenina (2012 film)|Anna Karenina]]''. Later that year, he starred as Ben in [[Oliver Stone]]'s ''[[Savages (2012 film)|Savages]]''. [[HitFix]] film critic Drew McWeeny was positive of the bond between Johnson and co-star [[Taylor Kitsch]], which \"seems not only credible but lived in and authentic throughout the film\", and noted the evolution in maturity of Johnson since ''Kick-Ass''.<ref>{{cite web|last=McWeeny|first=Drew|title=Review: Oliver Stone turns Aaron Johnson, Taylor Kitsch, and Blake Lively into 'Savages'|url=http://www.hitfix.com/motion-captured/review-oliver-stone-turns-aaron-johnson-taylor-kitsch-and-blake-lively-into-savages|work=[[HitFix]]|accessdate=24 August 2012|date=30 June 2012}}</ref> Taylor-Johnson starred in the ''[[Godzilla (2014 film)|Godzilla]]'' reboot, released in May 2014.<ref name=\"Godzilla1\">{{cite web|work=[[Variety (magazine)|Variety]] |url=https://variety.com/2013/film/news/elizabeth-olsen-bryan-cranston-circling-godzilla-1118065783/ |title=Elizabeth Olsen, Bryan Cranston circling 'Godzilla' |last=Kroll |first=Justin |date=6 February 2013 |accessdate=17 March 2014 |archivedate=13 March 2013 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20130313184951/http://variety.com/2013/film/news/elizabeth-olsen-bryan-cranston-circling-godzilla-1118065783/ |url-status=live }}</ref><ref name=\"Godzilla2\">{{cite web |work=[[Los Angeles Times]] |url=http://www.latimes.com/entertainment/movies/moviesnow/la-et-mn-godzilla-trailer-widespread-destruction-bryan-cranston-20140225,0,942729.story |title='Godzilla' trailer: Bryan Cranston panics, destruction rains down |last=Gettell |first=Oliver |date=25 February 2014 |accessdate=17 March 2014 |archivedate=26 February 2014 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20140226182729/http://www.latimes.com/entertainment/movies/moviesnow/la-et-mn-godzilla-trailer-widespread-destruction-bryan-cranston-20140225,0,942729.story#axzz2wDzJjMw7 |url-status=live }}</ref> Taylor-Johnson played [[Quicksilver (comics)|Quicksilver]] in ''[[Avengers: Age of Ultron]]'' (2015), the sequel to ''[[The Avengers (2012 film)|The Avengers]]''.<ref name=\"AgeofUltron\">{{cite web|url=http://marvel.com/news/story/21563/official_elizabeth_olsen_aaron_taylor-johnson_join_avengers_age_of_ultron |title=Official: Elizabeth Olsen & Aaron Taylor-Johnson Join 'Avengers: Age of Ultron' |publisher=Marvel |date=25 November 2013 |accessdate=25 November 2013 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20140108033705/http://marvel.com/news/movies/2013/11/25/21563/official_elizabeth_olsen_aaron_taylor-johnson_join_avengers_age_of_ultron |archivedate=8 January 2014 |url-status=live }}</ref> Taylor-Johnson first appeared as the character in a post-credits scene of the film ''[[Captain America: The Winter Soldier]]''.<ref name=\"WinterSoldier\">{{cite web|first=Jenna |last=Milly |date=14 March 2014 |title='Captain America: The Winter Soldier' premiere: Crossover is the word |url=http://popwatch.ew.com/2014/03/14/captain-america-the-winter-soldier-premiere/ |work=[[Entertainment Weekly]] |accessdate=17 March 2014 |archivedate=15 March 2014 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20140315010847/http://popwatch.ew.com/2014/03/14/captain-america-the-winter-soldier-premiere/ |url-status=live }}</ref> The role reunited him with [[Elizabeth Olsen]], who played his wife in ''Godzilla''.<ref name=\"Godzilla2\" /><ref name=\"AgeofUltron\" />\n\nIn 2016, he played Ray, a menacing Texan, in [[Tom Ford]]'s thriller ''[[Nocturnal Animals]]''. For the role, he won the [[Golden Globe Award for Best Supporting Actor \u2013 Motion Picture]]. Taylor-Johnson also became first Golden Globe Award for Best Supporting Actor winner since [[Richard Benjamin]] who did not receive an [[Academy Award]] nomination. For the role he also received a nomination for the [[BAFTA Award for Best Actor in a Supporting Role]]. In 2017, he played an American soldier (alongside [[John Cena]]) in [[Doug Liman]]'s thriller ''[[The Wall (2017 film)|The Wall]]'',<ref>{{cite news|last1=Kroll|first1=Justin|title=Aaron Taylor-Johnson Eyed for Lead in Doug Liman's 'The Wall' (EXCLUSIVE)|url=https://variety.com/2016/film/news/aaron-taylor-johnson-the-wall-doug-liman-1201769484/|accessdate=1 December 2016|work=Variety|date=9 May 2016}}</ref> and in 2018, he appeared in ''[[Outlaw King]]'', a British-American historical action drama about [[Robert the Bruce]] and the Wars of Scottish Independence. In May 2019, Taylor-Johnson was cast in [[Christopher Nolan]]\u2019s ''[[Tenet (film)|Tenet]]'', set for release in July 2020.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://deadline.com/2019/05/christopher-nolan-tenet-movie-cast-release-date-1202620596/|title=Christopher Nolan's New Movie Gets A Title, Final Cast As Shooting Begins|website=[[Deadline Hollywood]]|first=Patrick|last=Hipes|date=22 May 2019|accessdate=22 May 2019}}</ref>\n\nIn 2020, it was announced that Aaron Taylor Johnson will join [[Steve Pemberton]] on West End stage in [[The Pillowman]] play.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.ikonlondonmagazine.com/west-end-aaron-taylor-johnson-steve-pemberton-to-star-in-the-pillowman/|title=\nWest End: Aaron Taylor-Johnson & Steve Pemberton to Star in The Pillowman|publisher=Ikon London Magazine| first1 = Tamara|last1=Orlova-Alvarez | date=28 February 2020|accessdate=28 February 2020}}</ref> directed by Matthew Dunster.\n\n==Personal life==\n[[File:Sam Taylor-Wood & Aaron Johnson.jpg|thumb|right|150px|Taylor-Johnson, with Sam Taylor-Johnson, in September 2010]]\nAaron Johnson began a relationship with ''[[Nowhere Boy]]'' director [[Sam Taylor-Johnson|Sam Taylor-Wood]], after meeting on the 2009 set of the film when he was 18 and she was 42.<ref name=\"She's Having His Baby!\"/> They announced their engagement in October 2009 and married at [[Babington House]], Somerset, England on 21 June 2012. The two changed their surnames to \"Taylor-Johnson\" and use the surname professionally.<ref name=\"Buchanan\">{{cite web|last=Buchanan |first=Kyle |url=http://www.vulture.com/2012/06/aaron-johnson-sam-taylor-wood-marry.html |title=Aaron Johnson, Sam Taylor-Wood Marry |publisher=Vulture |accessdate=23 June 2012}}</ref><ref name=\"She's Having His Baby!\">{{cite magazine|url=http://www.people.com/people/archive/article/0,,20363616,00.html|title=She's Having His Baby!|magazine=People|date=3 May 2010|accessdate=25 January 2012}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.sheptonmalletjournal.co.uk/50-Shades-Grey-film-directed-Sam-Taylor-Johnson/story-19367650-detail/story.html |title=50 Shades of Grey film to be directed by Sam Taylor-Johnson |work=Shepton Mallet Journal |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20140522213458/http://www.sheptonmalletjournal.co.uk/50-Shades-Grey-film-directed-Sam-Taylor-Johnson/story-19367650-detail/story.html |archivedate=22 May 2014 }}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/news/celebritynews/6664818/Aaron-Johnson-fiance-of-artist-Sam-Taylor-Wood-considers-himself-a-very-lucky-man.html|title=Aaron Johnson, fianc\u00e9 of artist Sam Taylor-Wood, considers himself 'a very lucky man'|newspaper=The Telegraph|date=27 November 2009|accessdate=25 January 2012|location=London}}</ref> The couple have two daughters. He is also stepfather to two daughters from his wife's previous marriage.\n\nTaylor-Johnson was named one of [[GQ]]'s 50 best dressed British men in 2015.<ref>{{cite news|title=50 Best Dressed Men in Britain 2015 |url=http://www.gq-magazine.co.uk/style/articles/2015-01/05/best-dressed-men-2015/ |work=GQ |date=5 January 2015 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20150107145128/http://www.gq-magazine.co.uk/style/articles/2015-01/05/best-dressed-men-2015 |archivedate=7 January 2015 }}</ref>\n\n==Filmography==\n\n===Film===\n<!--do ''not'' use rowspans per WP:FILMOGRAPHY-->{|class=\"wikitable\"\n|+Key\n|style=\"background:#FFFFCC;\"| {{dagger|alt=Not yet released}}\n|Denotes works that have not yet been released\n|}\n{| class=\"wikitable sortable\"\n|-\n! Year\n! Title\n! Role\n! Director\n! class=\"unsortable\"| Notes\n|-\n| 2000\n| ''[[The Apocalypse (2000 film)|The Apocalypse]]''\n| Johanan\n| Raffaele Mertes\n|\n|-\n| 2002\n| ''[[Tom & Thomas]]''\n| Tom Sheppard / Thomas\n| Esm\u00e9 Lammers\n|\n|-\n| rowspan=\"2\" | 2003\n| ''[[Behind Closed Doors (2003 film)|Behind Closed Doors]]''\n| Sam Goodwin\n| Louis Caulfield\n|\n|-\n| ''[[Shanghai Knights]]''\n| [[Charlie Chaplin]]\n| [[David Dobkin (director)|David Dobkin]]\n|\n|-\n| 2004\n| ''[[Dead Cool]]''\n| George\n| David Cohen\n|\n|-\n| rowspan=\"4\" | 2006\n| ''{{sortname|The|Thief Lord|dab=film}}''\n| Prosper\n| Richard Claus\n|\n|-\n| ''{{sortname|The|Illusionist|dab=2006 film}}''\n| Young Eisenheim\n| [[Neil Burger]]\n|\n|-\n| ''Fast Learners''\n| Neil\n| [[Christoph R\u00f6hl]]\n| Short film\n|-\n| ''{{sortname|The|Best Man|The Best Man (2005 film)}}''\n| Michael (Aged 15)\n| Stefan Schwartz\n|\n|-\n| 2007\n| ''The Magic Door''\n| Flip\n| Paul Matthews\n| \n|-\n| rowspan=\"2\" | 2008\n| ''Dummy''\n| Danny\n| Matthew Thompson\n| Nominated \u2014 [[London Film Critics' Circle|ALFS Award for Young British Performer of the Year]]\n|-\n| ''[[Angus, Thongs and Perfect Snogging]]''\n| Robbie Jennings\n| [[Gurinder Chadha]]\n|\n|-\n| rowspan=\"2\" | 2009\n| ''{{sortname|The|Greatest|dab=2009 film}}''\n| Bennett Brewer\n| [[Shana Feste]]\n|\n|-\n| ''[[Nowhere Boy]]''\n| [[John Lennon]]\n| [[Sam Taylor-Johnson]]\n| [[Empire Award for Best Newcomer]]<br />Nominated \u2014 [[London Film Critics' Circle|ALFS Award for Young British Performer of the Year]]<br />Nominated \u2014 [[British Independent Film Awards|British Independent Film Award for Best Actor]]\n|-\n| rowspan=\"2\" | 2010\n| ''[[Kick-Ass (film)|Kick-Ass]]''\n| [[Kick-Ass (character)|David \"Dave\" Lizewski / Kick-Ass]]\n| [[Matthew Vaughn]]\n| Nominated \u2014 [[Empire Award for Best Actor]]<br />Nominated \u2014 [[BAFTA Rising Star Award]]<br />Nominated \u2014 [[2010 Scream Awards|Scream Award for Best Breakout Performance \u2013 Male]]<br />Nominated \u2014 [[2010 Scream Awards|Scream Award for Best Fantasy Actor]]<br />Nominated \u2014 [[2010 Scream Awards|Scream Award for Best Superhero]]<br />Nominated \u2014 [[2010 Teen Choice Awards|Teen Choice Award for Breakout Male]]\n|-\n| ''[[Chatroom (film)|Chatroom]]''\n| William Collins\n| [[Hideo Nakata]]\n|\n|-\n| 2011\n| ''[[Albert Nobbs]]''\n| Joe Mackins\n| [[Rodrigo Garc\u00eda (director)|Rodrigo Garc\u00eda]]\n| \n|-\n| rowspan=\"2\" | 2012\n| ''[[Savages (2012 film)|Savages]]''\n| Ben\n| [[Oliver Stone]]\n| \n|-\n| ''[[Anna Karenina (2012 film)|Anna Karenina]]''\n| Count Vronsky\n| [[Joe Wright]]\n| Final time credited as Aaron Johnson<br />Nominated \u2014 [[Alliance of Women Film Journalists]] Award for Best Depiction of Nudity, Sexuality, or Seduction <small>(shared w/ [[Keira Knightley]])</small>\n|-\n| 2013\n| ''[[Kick-Ass 2 (film)|Kick-Ass 2]]''\n| David \"Dave\" Lizewski / Kick-Ass\n| [[Jeff Wadlow]]\n| First time credited as Aaron Taylor-Johnson\n|-\n| rowspan=\"2\" | 2014\n| ''[[Captain America: The Winter Soldier]]''\n| [[Quicksilver (comics)|Pietro Maximoff / Quicksilver]]\n| [[Russo brothers|Anthony and Joe Russo]]\n| Uncredited cameo\n|-\n| ''[[Godzilla (2014 film)|Godzilla]]''\n| Lt. Ford Brody\n| [[Gareth Edwards (director)|Gareth Edwards]]\n|\n|-\n| 2015\n| ''[[Avengers: Age of Ultron]]''\n|Pietro Maximoff / Quicksilver\n| [[Joss Whedon]]\n|\n|-\n| 2016\n| ''[[Nocturnal Animals]]''\n| Ray Marcus\n| [[Tom Ford]]\n| [[Golden Globe Award for Best Supporting Actor \u2013 Motion Picture]]<br>[[Santa Barbara International Film Festival|Virtuosos Award for Best Supporting Actor]]<br>Nominated \u2014 [[BAFTA Award for Best Actor in a Supporting Role]]<br>Nominated \u2014 [[San Diego Film Critics Society Award for Best Supporting Actor]]\n|-\n| 2017\n| ''[[The Wall (2017 film)|The Wall]]''\n| Sgt. Allen \"Ize\" Isaac\n| [[Doug Liman]]\n| \n|-\n| rowspan=\"2\" | 2018\n| ''[[Outlaw King]]''\n| [[James Douglas, Lord of Douglas]]\n| [[David Mackenzie (director)|David Mackenzie]]\n| \n|-\n| ''[[A Million Little Pieces (film)|A Million Little Pieces]]''\n| [[James Frey]]\n| Sam Taylor-Johnson\n| Also writer\n|-\n| rowspan=\"2\" |2020\n|data-sort-value=\"King's Man, The\" scope=\"row\" style=\"background:#FFFFCC;\"|''[[The King's Man]]''{{dagger|alt=Not yet released}}\n|Lee Unwin\n|Matthew Vaughn\n|Post-production\n|-\n|scope=\"row\" style=\"background:#FFFFCC;\"|''[[Tenet (film)|Tenet]]''{{dagger|alt=Not yet released}}\n| TBA\n| [[Christopher Nolan]]\n| Post-production\n|}\n\n===Television===\n{| class=\"wikitable sortable\"\n|-\n! Year\n! Title\n! Role\n! class=\"unsortable\"| Notes\n|-\n| 2001\n| ''Armadillo''\n| Young Lorimer Black\n|\n|-\n| 2003\n| ''{{sortname|The|Bill}}''\n| Zac Clough\n| Episode: \"162\"\n|-\n| rowspan=\"2\" | 2004\n| ''Family Business''\n| Paul Sullivan\n| 1 episode\n|-\n| ''[[Feather Boy]]''\n| Niker\n| 3 episodes\n|-\n| rowspan=\"2\" | 2006\n| ''[[I Shouldn't Be Alive]]''\n| Mark\n| 4 episodes\n|-\n| ''[[Casualty (TV series)|Casualty]]''\n| Joey Byrne\n| Episode: \"Silent Ties\"\n|-\n| rowspan=\"4\" | 2007\n| ''[[Talk to Me (UK TV series)|Talk to Me]]''\n| Aaron\n| 4 episodes\n|-\n| ''[[Coming Up (TV series)|Coming Up]]''\n| Eoin\n| Episode: \"99,100\"\n|-\n| ''[[Nearly Famous]]''\n| Owen Stephens\n| 6 episodes\n|-\n| ''[[Sherlock Holmes and the Baker Street Irregulars]]''\n| Finch\n| Television film\n|-\n|}\n\n===Video games===\n<!--do ''not'' use rowspans per WP:FILMOGRAPHY-->\n{| class=\"wikitable sortable\"\n|-\n! Year\n! Title\n! Role\n! class=\"unsortable\"| Notes\n|-\n| 2010\n| ''[[Kick-Ass: The Game]]''\n| Kick-Ass (voice)\n| \n|}\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist|30em}}\n\n==External links==\n{{Commons category}}\n* {{IMDb name}}\n* {{Instagram}}\n\n{{Navboxes\n|title = Awards for Aaron Taylor-Johnson\n|list =\n{{Empire Award for Best Newcomer}}\n{{Glamour Awards Man of the Year}}\n{{Golden Globe Award Best Supporting Actor Motion Picture}}\n}}\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Taylor-Johnson, Aaron}}\n[[Category:1990 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:21st-century English male actors]]\n[[Category:Best Newcomer Empire Award winners]]\n[[Category:English male child actors]]\n[[Category:English male film actors]]\n[[Category:English male television actors]]\n[[Category:People from High Wycombe]]\n[[Category:English expatriates in the United States]]\n[[Category:Jewish English male actors]]\n[[Category:Best Supporting Actor Golden Globe (film) winners]]\n", "text_old": "{{Short description|English actor}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=March 2020}}\n{{EngvarB|date=March 2020}}\n{{Infobox person\n| name               = Aaron Taylor-Johnson\n| image              = Aaron Taylor-Johnson SDCC 2014 (cropped).jpg\n| caption            = Johnson at the 2014 [[San Diego Comic Con]]\n| birth_name         = Aaron Perry Johnson\n| birth_date         = {{Birth date and age|df=y|1990|6|13}}\n| birth_place        = [[High Wycombe]], Buckinghamshire, England\n| nationality        = British\n| othername          = Aaron Johnson\n| occupation         = Actor, screenwriter\n| years_active       = 2000\u2013present\n| children           = 2\n| spouse             = {{marriage|[[Sam Taylor-Johnson|Sam Taylor-Wood]]|2012}}\n}}\n'''Aaron Perry Taylor-Johnson''' (n\u00e9 '''Johnson''';<ref name=birth>''Births, Marriages & Deaths Index of England & Wales, 1916\u20132005.''; at ancestry.com</ref> born 13 June 1990)<ref name=TimesOnline/><ref name=UKTVGuide/> is an English<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.standard.co.uk/lifestyle/esmagazine/aaron-taylor-johnson-i-was-raised-by-women-now-i-m-raising-women-and-sam-s-the-best-woman-i-know-9323936.html|title=Aaron Taylor-Johnson: 'I was raised by women. Now I\u2019m raising women. And Sam's the best woman I know'|work=London Evening Standard|date=8 May 2014|last=Rafanelli|first=Stephanie|accessdate=9 December 2019}}</ref> actor and screenwriter, best known for his portrayal of the [[Kick-Ass (character)|titular character]] in the ''[[Kick-Ass (film)|Kick-Ass]]'' films and [[Quicksilver (comics)|Quicksilver]] in ''[[Avengers: Age of Ultron]]'' (2015).\n\nTaylor-Johnson began performing at age six and has appeared in films such as ''[[Shanghai Knights]]'' (2003), playing a young [[Charlie Chaplin]], ''[[The Illusionist (2006 film)|The Illusionist]]'' (2006) and ''[[Angus, Thongs and Perfect Snogging]]'' (2008). He had his breakthrough performance in the [[John Lennon]] biopic ''[[Nowhere Boy]]'' (2009). He went on to portray Ben in the [[Oliver Stone]]-directed crime thriller ''[[Savages (2012 film)|Savages]]'' (2012), Russian aristocrat Count Vronsky in [[Joe Wright]]'s adaptation of ''[[Anna Karenina (2012 film)|Anna Karenina]]'' (2012) and Lt. Brody in [[Gareth Edwards (director)|Gareth Edwards]]' monster movie ''[[Godzilla (2014 film)|Godzilla]]'' (2014). For his performance as psychopathic drifter Ray Marcus in [[Tom Ford]]'s thriller ''[[Nocturnal Animals]]'' (2016), he won the [[Golden Globe Award for Best Supporting Actor \u2013 Motion Picture|Golden Globe Award for Best Supporting Actor]] and was nominated for the [[BAFTA Award for Best Actor in a Supporting Role]].\n\n==Early life==\nAaron Perry Johnson was born in [[High Wycombe]], Buckinghamshire,<ref>{{cite news |url= https://www.nytimes.com/movies/person/893722/Aaron-Johnson/biography |title= Aaron Johnson biography |work= NYTimes.com Movies & TV |publisher= [[The New York Times]] ([[AllMovie|All Movie Guide]] and [[Baseline (database)|Baseline]]) |accessdate= 29 October 2011}}</ref> the son of Sarah and Robert Johnson, a [[housewife]] mother and civil engineer father, respectively.<ref name=UKTVGuide>{{cite web|url=http://uk-tv-guide.com/celebrity/Aaron+Johnson/103417|archive-url=https://archive.today/20130913180604/http://uk-tv-guide.com/celebrity/Aaron+Johnson/103417|url-status=dead|archive-date=13 September 2013|title=Aaron Johnson profile|publisher=Uk-tv-guide.com|accessdate=26 October 2011}}</ref><ref name=\"timesref02\">{{cite news|last=Maher|first=Kevin|title=Aaron Johnson: Beatle mania|newspaper=The Times|date=3 October 2009|url=http://entertainment.timesonline.co.uk/tol/arts_and_entertainment/film/london_film_festival/article6852334.ece?print=yes&randnum=1151003209000|accessdate=24 April 2010|location=London}}</ref> He has a sister, Gemma, who appeared in his film ''[[Tom & Thomas]]'' (2002) in a small role.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://myeveryzine.com/story/10-things-know-about-aaron-johnson/|title=10 Things to Know About Aaron Johnson|first=Grace|last=Gavilanes|date=8 July 2012}}</ref> He is [[British Jews|Jewish]].<ref>{{cite news | url=https://www.theguardian.com/film/2015/apr/23/aaron-taylor-johnson-avengers-age-ultron-interview | title=Aaron Taylor-Johnson: 'Changing my name felt beautiful' | newspaper=[[The Guardian]] | date=23 April 2015 | accessdate=9 August 2015 | author=Gilbey, Ryan|quote=He liked it recently when someone said he resembled a fashionable Hasidic Jew. \u201cThat was nice because I have really curly hair and also I\u2019m Jewish,\u201d he explains.}}</ref> He was educated at [[Holmer Green Senior School]]<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.hgss.co.uk/default.aspx?id=373|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20150404070713/http://www.hgss.co.uk/default.aspx?id=373|url-status=dead|title=Hgss.co.uk|archivedate=4 April 2015}}</ref> and attended the Jackie Palmer Stage School in High Wycombe between 1996 and 2008, where he studied drama, tap, jazz, acrobatics, and singing.<ref>{{cite news |first=Rebecca |last=Cain |title=Another successful year for the Jackie Palmer Stage School and agency|url=http://www.bucksfreepress.co.uk/news/4829177.Wycombe_s_stage_school_s_pupils_star_on_TV/ |newspaper=[[Bucks Free Press]] |date=3 January 2010 |accessdate=3 January 2010}}</ref>\n\n==Career==\nTaylor-Johnson began acting at the age of six. On stage, he appeared in a London production of [[Shakespeare]]'s ''[[Macbeth]]'', playing the son of [[Macduff (Macbeth)|Macduff]] alongside [[Rufus Sewell]], who played [[Macbeth]], in 1999.<ref>{{cite web |title=Sewell to Return to Stage in Macbeth |url=http://www.whatsonstage.com/news/theatre/london/E0607221502/Rufus+Sewell+to+Return+to+Stage+in+Macbeth.html |archivedate=12 April 2013 |archiveurl=https://archive.today/20130412044133/http://www.whatsonstage.com/news/theatre/london/E0607221502/Rufus+Sewell+to+Return+to+Stage+in+Macbeth.html |url-status=dead |access-date=16 February 2013 }}</ref> He appeared in [[Arthur Miller]]\u2019s ''[[All My Sons]]'' in 2000. His television roles have included Niker in the 2004 [[BBC]] adaptation of the novel ''[[Feather Boy]]'', Aaron in [[Danny Brocklehurst]]'s [[ITV1]] serial ''[[Talk to Me (UK TV series)|Talk to Me]]'', and Owen Stephens in ''[[Nearly Famous]]''.<ref name=TimesOnline>{{cite news|url=http://entertainment.timesonline.co.uk/tol/arts_and_entertainment/film/article6953190.ece|title=The Times: Entertainment|work=The Times|accessdate=26 October 2011|location=London|first=Sadie |last=Gray}}</ref> In 2003, Taylor-Johnson appeared as a young [[Charlie Chaplin]] in ''[[Shanghai Knights]]'', with Chaplin depicted as a member of a London gang of street thugs. In 2006, he appeared in ''[[The Illusionist (2006 film)|The Illusionist]]'', appearing in the early flashback scenes as [[Edward Norton]]'s character, Eduard Abramovicz, as a teenager. The scenes show the young Eduard as he first learns magic, and to do this, Johnson had to learn how to perform the ball trick displayed by his character. He learned how to perform the balancing of the egg on the stick, although that was effected mechanically.<ref>Writer/director [[Neil Burger]] explains this on the film's DVD commentary.</ref> Also in 2006, he starred in the film ''[[The Thief Lord (film)|The Thief Lord]]'', as Prosper.\n[[File:Aaron Taylor-Johnson by Gage Skidmore.jpg|thumb|left|150px|Johnson at the 2013 [[San Diego Comic-Con]] promoting ''[[Godzilla (2014 film)|Godzilla'']]'']]\nTaylor-Johnson appeared as [[John Lennon]] in the 2009 biographical film film ''[[Nowhere Boy]]'', directed by [[Sam Taylor-Wood]]. His performance saw him receive the [[Empire Award for Best Newcomer]] and he was also nominated for [[London Film Critics Circle Awards 2009#Young British Performer of the Year|Young British Performer of the Year]] by the [[London Film Critics' Circle]]. In 2010, Taylor-Johnson appeared as [[Kick-Ass (character)|David \"Dave\" Lizewski/Kick-Ass]], the lead character in ''[[Kick-Ass (film)|Kick-Ass]]'', based on the [[Kick-Ass (comic)|superhero comic book of the same name]] by Scottish writer [[Mark Millar]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.aintitcool.com/node/43367 |title=Ain't It Cool News: The best in movie, TV, DVD, and comic book news |publisher=Aintitcool.com|accessdate=26 October 2011}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|last=Gholson|first=John |url=http://www.scifisquad.com/2009/12/14/kick-ass-kicks-ass-at-bnat|title='Kick-Ass' Kicks Ass at BNAT \u2013 The Moviefone Blog|publisher=Scifisquad.com|date=2 May 2011|accessdate=26 October 2011}}</ref> His performance in ''Kick-Ass'' saw him nominated for the [[BAFTA Rising Star Award]]. He has also appeared as the central character, William, in [[Hideo Nakata]]'s ''[[Chatroom (film)|Chatroom]]''.<ref name=TimesOnline/> In December 2010, Taylor-Johnson joined the cast of ''[[Albert Nobbs]]'' as a replacement for [[Orlando Bloom]], who dropped out of the production due to his wife's pregnancy.<ref name=nobbs>{{cite web|last=Sneider|first=Jeff|url=http://www.thewrap.com/node/23054|title=Aaron Johnson Joins Mia Wasikowska in 'Albert Nobbs'|publisher=Thewrap.com|date=6 December 2010|accessdate=26 October 2011}}</ref> Taylor-Johnson starred in [[R.E.M.]]'s 2011 music video \"[[\u00dcberlin]]\", which was also directed by his then-fianc\u00e9e.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.theguardian.com/music/video/2011/mar/02/rem-uberlin|title=Watch REM's Uberlin, starring Aaron Johnson \u2013 video|newspaper=The Guardian|date=2 March 2011|accessdate=4 December 2011|location=London}}</ref>\n\nIn 2012, Taylor-Johnson played Count Vronsky in ''[[Anna Karenina (2012 film)|Anna Karenina]]''. Later that year, he starred as Ben in [[Oliver Stone]]'s ''[[Savages (2012 film)|Savages]]''. [[HitFix]] film critic Drew McWeeny was positive of the bond between Johnson and co-star [[Taylor Kitsch]], which \"seems not only credible but lived in and authentic throughout the film\", and noted the evolution in maturity of Johnson since ''Kick-Ass''.<ref>{{cite web|last=McWeeny|first=Drew|title=Review: Oliver Stone turns Aaron Johnson, Taylor Kitsch, and Blake Lively into 'Savages'|url=http://www.hitfix.com/motion-captured/review-oliver-stone-turns-aaron-johnson-taylor-kitsch-and-blake-lively-into-savages|work=[[HitFix]]|accessdate=24 August 2012|date=30 June 2012}}</ref> Taylor-Johnson starred in the ''[[Godzilla (2014 film)|Godzilla]]'' reboot, released in May 2014.<ref name=\"Godzilla1\">{{cite web|work=[[Variety (magazine)|Variety]] |url=https://variety.com/2013/film/news/elizabeth-olsen-bryan-cranston-circling-godzilla-1118065783/ |title=Elizabeth Olsen, Bryan Cranston circling 'Godzilla' |last=Kroll |first=Justin |date=6 February 2013 |accessdate=17 March 2014 |archivedate=13 March 2013 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20130313184951/http://variety.com/2013/film/news/elizabeth-olsen-bryan-cranston-circling-godzilla-1118065783/ |url-status=live }}</ref><ref name=\"Godzilla2\">{{cite web |work=[[Los Angeles Times]] |url=http://www.latimes.com/entertainment/movies/moviesnow/la-et-mn-godzilla-trailer-widespread-destruction-bryan-cranston-20140225,0,942729.story |title='Godzilla' trailer: Bryan Cranston panics, destruction rains down |last=Gettell |first=Oliver |date=25 February 2014 |accessdate=17 March 2014 |archivedate=26 February 2014 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20140226182729/http://www.latimes.com/entertainment/movies/moviesnow/la-et-mn-godzilla-trailer-widespread-destruction-bryan-cranston-20140225,0,942729.story#axzz2wDzJjMw7 |url-status=live }}</ref> Taylor-Johnson played [[Quicksilver (comics)|Quicksilver]] in ''[[Avengers: Age of Ultron]]'' (2015), the sequel to ''[[The Avengers (2012 film)|The Avengers]]''.<ref name=\"AgeofUltron\">{{cite web|url=http://marvel.com/news/story/21563/official_elizabeth_olsen_aaron_taylor-johnson_join_avengers_age_of_ultron |title=Official: Elizabeth Olsen & Aaron Taylor-Johnson Join 'Avengers: Age of Ultron' |publisher=Marvel |date=25 November 2013 |accessdate=25 November 2013 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20140108033705/http://marvel.com/news/movies/2013/11/25/21563/official_elizabeth_olsen_aaron_taylor-johnson_join_avengers_age_of_ultron |archivedate=8 January 2014 |url-status=live }}</ref> Taylor-Johnson first appeared as the character in a post-credits scene of the film ''[[Captain America: The Winter Soldier]]''.<ref name=\"WinterSoldier\">{{cite web|first=Jenna |last=Milly |date=14 March 2014 |title='Captain America: The Winter Soldier' premiere: Crossover is the word |url=http://popwatch.ew.com/2014/03/14/captain-america-the-winter-soldier-premiere/ |work=[[Entertainment Weekly]] |accessdate=17 March 2014 |archivedate=15 March 2014 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20140315010847/http://popwatch.ew.com/2014/03/14/captain-america-the-winter-soldier-premiere/ |url-status=live }}</ref> The role reunited him with [[Elizabeth Olsen]], who played his wife in ''Godzilla''.<ref name=\"Godzilla2\" /><ref name=\"AgeofUltron\" />\n\nIn 2016, he played Ray, a menacing Texan, in [[Tom Ford]]'s thriller ''[[Nocturnal Animals]]''. For the role, he won the [[Golden Globe Award for Best Supporting Actor \u2013 Motion Picture]]. Taylor-Johnson also became first Golden Globe Award for Best Supporting Actor winner since [[Richard Benjamin]] who did not receive an [[Academy Award]] nomination. For the role he also received a nomination for the [[BAFTA Award for Best Actor in a Supporting Role]]. In 2017, he played an American soldier (alongside [[John Cena]]) in [[Doug Liman]]'s thriller ''[[The Wall (2017 film)|The Wall]]'',<ref>{{cite news|last1=Kroll|first1=Justin|title=Aaron Taylor-Johnson Eyed for Lead in Doug Liman's 'The Wall' (EXCLUSIVE)|url=https://variety.com/2016/film/news/aaron-taylor-johnson-the-wall-doug-liman-1201769484/|accessdate=1 December 2016|work=Variety|date=9 May 2016}}</ref> and in 2018, he appeared in ''[[Outlaw King]]'', a British-American historical action drama about [[Robert the Bruce]] and the Wars of Scottish Independence. In May 2019, Taylor-Johnson was cast in [[Christopher Nolan]]\u2019s ''[[Tenet (film)|Tenet]]'', set for release in July 2020.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://deadline.com/2019/05/christopher-nolan-tenet-movie-cast-release-date-1202620596/|title=Christopher Nolan's New Movie Gets A Title, Final Cast As Shooting Begins|website=[[Deadline Hollywood]]|first=Patrick|last=Hipes|date=22 May 2019|accessdate=22 May 2019}}</ref>\n\nIn 2020, it was announced that Aaron Taylor Johnson will join [[Steve Pemberton]] on West End stage in [[The Pillowman]] play.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.ikonlondonmagazine.com/west-end-aaron-taylor-johnson-steve-pemberton-to-star-in-the-pillowman/|title=\nWest End: Aaron Taylor-Johnson & Steve Pemberton to Star in The Pillowman|publisher=Ikon London Magazine| first1 = Tamara|last1=Orlova-Alvarez | date=28 February 2020|accessdate=28 February 2020}}</ref> directed by Matthew Dunster.\n\n==Personal life==\n[[File:Sam Taylor-Wood & Aaron Johnson.jpg|thumb|right|150px|Taylor-Johnson, with Sam Taylor-Johnson, in September 2010]]\nAaron Johnson began a relationship with ''[[Nowhere Boy]]'' director [[Sam Taylor-Johnson|Sam Taylor-Wood]], after meeting on the 2009 set of the film when he was 18 and she was 42.<ref name=\"She's Having His Baby!\"/> They announced their engagement in October 2009 and married at [[Babington House]], Somerset, England on 21 June 2012. The two changed their surnames to \"Taylor-Johnson\" and use the surname professionally.<ref name=\"Buchanan\">{{cite web|last=Buchanan |first=Kyle |url=http://www.vulture.com/2012/06/aaron-johnson-sam-taylor-wood-marry.html |title=Aaron Johnson, Sam Taylor-Wood Marry |publisher=Vulture |accessdate=23 June 2012}}</ref><ref name=\"She's Having His Baby!\">{{cite magazine|url=http://www.people.com/people/archive/article/0,,20363616,00.html|title=She's Having His Baby!|magazine=People|date=3 May 2010|accessdate=25 January 2012}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.sheptonmalletjournal.co.uk/50-Shades-Grey-film-directed-Sam-Taylor-Johnson/story-19367650-detail/story.html |title=50 Shades of Grey film to be directed by Sam Taylor-Johnson |work=Shepton Mallet Journal |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20140522213458/http://www.sheptonmalletjournal.co.uk/50-Shades-Grey-film-directed-Sam-Taylor-Johnson/story-19367650-detail/story.html |archivedate=22 May 2014 }}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/news/celebritynews/6664818/Aaron-Johnson-fiance-of-artist-Sam-Taylor-Wood-considers-himself-a-very-lucky-man.html|title=Aaron Johnson, fianc\u00e9 of artist Sam Taylor-Wood, considers himself 'a very lucky man'|newspaper=The Telegraph|date=27 November 2009|accessdate=25 January 2012|location=London}}</ref> The couple have two daughters. He is also stepfather to two daughters from his wife's previous marriage.\n\nTaylor-Johnson was named one of [[GQ]]'s 50 best dressed British men in 2015.<ref>{{cite news|title=50 Best Dressed Men in Britain 2015 |url=http://www.gq-magazine.co.uk/style/articles/2015-01/05/best-dressed-men-2015/ |work=GQ |date=5 January 2015 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20150107145128/http://www.gq-magazine.co.uk/style/articles/2015-01/05/best-dressed-men-2015 |archivedate=7 January 2015 }}</ref>\n\n==Filmography==\n\n===Film===\n<!--do ''not'' use rowspans per WP:FILMOGRAPHY-->{|class=\"wikitable\"\n|+Key\n|style=\"background:#FFFFCC;\"| {{dagger|alt=Not yet released}}\n|Denotes works that have not yet been released\n|}\n{| class=\"wikitable sortable\"\n|-\n! Year\n! Title\n! Role\n! Director\n! class=\"unsortable\"| Notes\n|-