Awards|Scream Award for Best Fantasy Actor]]<br />Nominated \u2014 [[2010 Scream Awards|Scream Award for Best Superhero]]<br />Nominated \u2014 [[2010 Teen Choice Awards|Teen Choice Award for Breakout Male]]\n|-\n| ''[[Chatroom (film)|Chatroom]]''\n| William Collins\n| [[Hideo Nakata]]\n|\n|-\n| 2011\n| ''[[Albert Nobbs]]''\n| Joe Mackins\n| [[Rodrigo Garc\u00eda (director)|Rodrigo Garc\u00eda]]\n| \n|-\n| rowspan=\"2\" | 2012\n| ''[[Savages (2012 film)|Savages]]''\n| Ben\n| [[Oliver Stone]]\n| \n|-\n| ''[[Anna Karenina (2012 film)|Anna Karenina]]''\n| Count Vronsky\n| [[Joe Wright]]\n| Final time credited as Aaron Johnson<br />Nominated \u2014 [[Alliance of Women Film Journalists]] Award for Best Depiction of Nudity, Sexuality, or Seduction <small>(shared w/ [[Keira Knightley]])</small>\n|-\n| 2013\n| ''[[Kick-Ass 2 (film)|Kick-Ass 2]]''\n| David \"Dave\" Lizewski / Kick-Ass\n| [[Jeff Wadlow]]\n| First time credited as Aaron Taylor-Johnson\n|-\n| rowspan=\"2\" | 2014\n| ''[[Captain America: The Winter Soldier]]''\n| [[Quicksilver (comics)|Pietro Maximoff / Quicksilver]]\n| [[Russo brothers|Anthony and Joe Russo]]\n| Uncredited cameo\n|-\n| ''[[Godzilla (2014 film)|Godzilla]]''\n| Lt. Ford Brody\n| [[Gareth Edwards (director)|Gareth Edwards]]\n|\n|-\n| 2015\n| ''[[Avengers: Age of Ultron]]''\n|Pietro Maximoff / Quicksilver\n| [[Joss Whedon]]\n|\n|-\n| 2016\n| ''[[Nocturnal Animals]]''\n| Ray Marcus\n| [[Tom Ford]]\n| [[Golden Globe Award for Best Supporting Actor \u2013 Motion Picture]]<br>[[Santa Barbara International Film Festival|Virtuosos Award for Best Supporting Actor]]<br>Nominated \u2014 [[BAFTA Award for Best Actor in a Supporting Role]]<br>Nominated \u2014 [[San Diego Film Critics Society Award for Best Supporting Actor]]\n|-\n| 2017\n| ''[[The Wall (2017 film)|The Wall]]''\n| Sgt. Allen \"Ize\" Isaac\n| [[Doug Liman]]\n| \n|-\n| rowspan=\"2\" | 2018\n| ''[[Outlaw King]]''\n| [[James Douglas, Lord of Douglas]]\n| [[David Mackenzie (director)|David Mackenzie]]\n| \n|-\n| ''[[A Million Little Pieces (film)|A Million Little Pieces]]''\n| [[James Frey]]\n| Sam Taylor-Johnson\n| Also writer\n|-\n| rowspan=\"2\" |2020\n|data-sort-value=\"King's Man, The\" scope=\"row\" style=\"background:#FFFFCC;\"|''[[The King's Man]]''{{dagger|alt=Not yet released}}\n|Lee Unwin\n|Matthew Vaughn\n|Post-production\n|-\n|scope=\"row\" style=\"background:#FFFFCC;\"|''[[Tenet (film)|Tenet]]''{{dagger|alt=Not yet released}}\n| TBA\n| [[Christopher Nolan]]\n| Post-production\n|}\n\n===Television===\n{| class=\"wikitable sortable\"\n|-\n! Year\n! Title\n! Role\n! class=\"unsortable\"| Notes\n|-\n| 2001\n| ''Armadillo''\n| Young Lorimer Black\n|\n|-\n| 2003\n| ''{{sortname|The|Bill}}''\n| Zac Clough\n| Episode: \"162\"\n|-\n| rowspan=\"2\" | 2004\n| ''Family Business''\n| Paul Sullivan\n| 1 episode\n|-\n| ''[[Feather Boy]]''\n| Niker\n| 3 episodes\n|-\n| rowspan=\"2\" | 2006\n| ''[[I Shouldn't Be Alive]]''\n| Mark\n| 4 episodes\n|-\n| ''[[Casualty (TV series)|Casualty]]''\n| Joey Byrne\n| Episode: \"Silent Ties\"\n|-\n| rowspan=\"4\" | 2007\n| ''[[Talk to Me (UK TV series)|Talk to Me]]''\n| Aaron\n| 4 episodes\n|-\n| ''[[Coming Up (TV series)|Coming Up]]''\n| Eoin\n| Episode: \"99,100\"\n|-\n| ''[[Nearly Famous]]''\n| Owen Stephens\n| 6 episodes\n|-\n| ''[[Sherlock Holmes and the Baker Street Irregulars]]''\n| Finch\n| Television film\n|-\n|}\n\n===Video games===\n<!--do ''not'' use rowspans per WP:FILMOGRAPHY-->\n{| class=\"wikitable sortable\"\n|-\n! Year\n! Title\n! Role\n! class=\"unsortable\"| Notes\n|-\n| 2010\n| ''[[Kick-Ass: The Game]]''\n| Kick-Ass (voice)\n| \n|}\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist|30em}}\n\n==External links==\n{{Commons category}}\n* {{IMDb name}}\n* {{Instagram}}\n\n{{Navboxes\n|title = Awards for Aaron Taylor-Johnson\n|list =\n{{Empire Award for Best Newcomer}}\n{{Glamour Awards Man of the Year}}\n{{Golden Globe Award Best Supporting Actor Motion Picture}}\n}}\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Taylor-Johnson, Aaron}}\n[[Category:1990 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:21st-century English male actors]]\n[[Category:Best Newcomer Empire Award winners]]\n[[Category:English male child actors]]\n[[Category:English male film actors]]\n[[Category:English male television actors]]\n[[Category:People from High Wycombe]]\n[[Category:English expatriates in the United States]]\n[[Category:Jewish English male actors]]\n[[Category:Best Supporting Actor Golden Globe (film) winners]]\n", "name_user": "2601:647:4300:dfc0::d7ab", "label": "unsafe", "comment": "", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Aaron_Taylor-Johnson"}
{"title_page": "Illegal immigration to the United States and crime", "text_new": "{{lead too short|date=February 2019}}\n{{Use mdy dates|date=March 2019}}\n\nThe issue of crimes committed by [[Illegal immigration to the United States|Illegal immigrants to the United States]] is a topic that is often asserted and debated in politics and the media when discussing [[Immigration policy in the United States]].\n\n== Research ==\n\n=== Relationship between immigration status and crime ===\nAccording to empirical evidence, immigrants (including illegal immigrants) are less likely to commit crimes than native-born [[Citizenship of the United States|citizens in the United States]].<ref name=\":25\">{{Cite news|url=http://econofact.org/are-immigrants-more-likely-to-commit-crimes|title=Are immigrants more likely to commit crimes? {{!}} Econofact|date=February 14, 2017|newspaper=Econofact|access-date=February 15, 2017|language=en-US}}</ref><ref name=\":20\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/politics/2017/live-updates/trump-white-house/real-time-fact-checking-and-analysis-of-trumps-address-to-congress/trump-calls-for-creation-of-office-to-support-victims-of-crimes-by-illegal-immigrants/|title=Trump calls for creation of office to support victims of crimes by illegal immigrants|website=Washington Post|access-date=May 4, 2017|quote=On the campaign trail, Trump said he would seek to quickly deport between 2 million and 3 million immigrants with criminal records. But a study by the Migration Policy Institute found that 820,000 unauthorized immigrants had committed other crimes, including about 300,000 with felony records}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.ppic.org/main/publication.asp?i=776|title=Crime, Corrections, and California: What Does Immigration Have to Do with It? (PPIC Publication)|website=www.ppic.org|access-date=June 23, 2016}}</ref><ref name=\":22\">{{Cite journal|last=Gonzalez|first=Benjamin|last2=Collingwood|first2=Loren|last3=El-Khatib|first3=Stephen Omar|date=May 7, 2017|title=The Politics of Refuge: Sanctuary Cities, Crime, and Undocumented Immigration |journal=Urban Affairs Review|volume=55|language=en|doi=10.1177/1078087417704974|page=107808741770497}} Quote: \"most studies have shown that undocumented immigrants tend to commit less crime than the native born\"</ref><ref name=\":21\">{{Cite news|url=http://www.politifact.com/truth-o-meter/statements/2015/jul/06/donald-trump/trump-immigration-claim-has-no-data-back-it/|title=Trump immigration claim has no data to back it up|work=PolitiFact|quote=... every expert we polled said there is a consensus among scholars that undocumented immigrants are not more likely to commit crimes than U.S. citizens.|access-date=August 22, 2017|language=en}}</ref>\n\nA 2018 study found that undocumented immigration to the United States did not increase [[violent crime]] rates.<ref>{{Cite journal|last=Light|first=Michael T.|last2=Miller|first2=TY|title=Does Undocumented Immigration Increase Violent Crime?|journal=Criminology|language=en|volume=56|issue=2|pages=370\u2013401|doi=10.1111/1745-9125.12175|pmid=30464356|pmc=6241529|issn=1745-9125|year=2018}}</ref> A 2017 study found that \"Increased undocumented immigration was significantly associated with reductions in drug arrests, drug overdose deaths, and DUI arrests, net of other factors.\"<ref>{{Cite journal|last=Light|first=Michael T.|last2=Miller|first2=Ty|last3=Kelly|first3=Brian C.|date=July 20, 2017|title=Undocumented Immigration, Drug Problems, and Driving Under the Influence in the United States, 1990\u20132014|journal=American Journal of Public Health|pages=e1\u2013e7|doi=10.2105/AJPH.2017.303884|pmid=28727520|pmc=5551598|issn=0090-0036|volume=107|issue=9}}</ref> A 2017 study found that California's extension of driving licenses to unauthorized immigrants \"did not increase the total number of accidents or the occurrence of fatal accidents, but it did reduce the likelihood of hit and run accidents, thereby improving traffic safety and reducing costs for California drivers ... providing unauthorized immigrants with access to driver's licenses can create positive externalities for the communities in which they live.\"<ref>{{Cite journal|last=Lueders|first=Hans|last2=Hainmueller|first2=Jens|last3=Lawrence|first3=Duncan|date=April 18, 2017|title=Providing driver's licenses to unauthorized immigrants in California improves traffic safety|journal=Proceedings of the National Academy of Sciences|language=en|volume=114|issue=16|pages=4111\u20134116|doi=10.1073/pnas.1618991114|issn=0027-8424|pmid=28373538|pmc=5402447}}</ref>\n\nA 2018 study in the ''[[American Economic Journal|American Economic Journal: Economic Policy]]'' found that by restricting the employment opportunities for unauthorized immigrants, the [[Immigration Reform and Control Act of 1986]] (IRCA) likely caused an increase in crime rates.<ref>{{Cite journal|first=Matthew|last=Freedman|first2=Emily|last2=Owens|first3=Sarah|last3=Bohn|title=Immigration, Employment Opportunities, and Criminal Behavior |journal=American Economic Journal: Economic Policy|volume=10|issue=2|pages=117\u2013151|language=en|doi=10.1257/pol.20150165|issn=1945-7731|year=2018|doi-access=free}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=http://faculty.sites.uci.edu/freedman/files/2017/06/FreedmanOwensBohn_Manuscript.pdf|title=Immigration, Employment Opportunities, and Criminal Behavior|last=|first=|date=|website=|access-date=}}</ref> A 2018 ''[[PLOS One]]'' study estimated that the undocumented immigrant population in the United States was 22 million, approximately twice as large as the estimate derived from the\n[[United States Census Bureau]]'s figures. An author of the study notes that this has implications for the relationship between undocumented immigration and crime, suggesting that the crime rate among undocumented immigrants is significantly lower than previously estimated: \"You have the same number of crimes but now spread over twice as many people as was believed before, which right away means that the crime rate among undocumented immigrants is essentially half whatever was previously believed.\"<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://thehill.com/latino/407848-yale-mit-study-22-million-not-11-million-undocumented-immigrants-in-us|title=Yale, MIT study: 22 million, not 11 million, undocumented immigrants in US|last=Garcia|first=Eric|date=September 21, 2018|website=TheHill|language=en|access-date=December 28, 2018}}</ref>\n\nAccording to analysis of the [[2010 United States Census]], \"immigrants to the United States are significantly less likely than native-born citizens to be incarcerated. The authors found that 1.6 percent of immigrant males age 18-39 are incarcerated, compared to 3.3 percent of the native-born... The divide was even sharper when the authors examined the incarceration rate among immigrant men the authors believe likely to be undocumented \u2014 specifically less-educated men from [[El Salvador]] and [[Guatemala]] between age 18-29. ... According to the analysis, these likely undocumented immigrants had an incarceration rate of 1.7 percent, compared with 10.7 percent for native-born men without a high school diploma\".<ref>{{cite news |last1=JULIA DAHL |title=How big a problem is crime committed by immigrants? |url=https://www.cbsnews.com/news/illegal-immigrants-and-crime-how-big-a-problem-is-crime-committed-by-immigrants/ |accessdate=February 23, 2019 |work=CBS News |date=January 27, 2017 |quote=}}</ref>\n\nA 2018 study found no evidence that apprehensions of undocumented immigrants in districts in the United States reduced crime rates.<ref>{{Cite journal|last=|first=|date=2018|title=Do Apprehensions of Undocumented Immigrants Reduce Crime and Create Jobs? Evidence from U.S. Districts, 2000-2015|url=https://lawreview.law.ucdavis.edu/issues/52/1/Symposium/52-1_Hines_Peri.pdf|journal=UC Davis Law Review|volume=|pages=|via=}}</ref>\n\nAccording to immigration analyst [[Alex Nowrasteh]], and criminologist [[Barry Latzer]], [[Texas]] is the only state that tracks illegal immigrants by the specific crime committed.<ref name=\"NowrastehCrime\"/><ref name=\"NowrastehRate\"/><ref name=\"LatzerRates\">{{cite news |last1=Latzer |first1=Barry |title=Do Illegal Aliens Have High Crime Rates? |url=https://www.city-journal.org/illegal-alien-crime-rate-data |accessdate=February 28, 2019 |publisher=[[City Journal]] |date=January 24, 2019}}</ref>  Homicide data are regarded as more accurate than data on other crimes because \"a much higher proportion of murders are solved.\"<ref name=\"LatzerRates\"/> The Texas data for 2016 showed that the rate of murder convictions in 2016 was 3.2 per 100,000 native-born Americans, 0.9 for every 100,000 legal immigrants and 1.8 per 100,000 illegal immigrants.<ref name=\"NowrastehCrime\">{{cite news |last1=Nowrasteh |first1=Alex |title=The Murder of Mollie Tibbetts and Illegal Immigrant Crime |url=https://www.cato.org/blog/murder-mollie-tibbetts-illegal-immigrant-crime-facts |accessdate=February 15, 2019 |publisher=[[Cato Institute]] |date=August 22, 2018}}</ref><ref name=\"NowrastehRate\">{{cite news |last1=Nowrasteh |first1=Alez |title=Everything is Bigger in Texas \u2014 except the illegal immigrant crime rate |url=https://www.houstonchronicle.com/opinion/outlook/article/Everything-is-Bigger-in-Texas-Except-the-12747805.php |accessdate=February 15, 2019 |work=Houston Chronicle |date=March 12, 2018}}</ref>\n\n===Others===\nA 2016 study of an effort to reduce crime in [[North Carolina]] by identifying and deporting illegal immigrants showed no correlation between increased deportation enforcement and local crime rates.<ref>Forrester, Andrew, and Alex Nowrasteh. Do Immigration Enforcement Programs Reduce Crime?: Evidence from the 287(g) Program in North Carolina. Cato Institute, 2018, www.jstor.org/stable/resrep16983.</ref>\n\n==Procedures==\nIndividuals who are in the United States illegally and who have been convicted of crimes are eligible to be deported under federal law.{{citation needed|date=March 2019}} Research suggests that immigration enforcement has no impact on crime rates.<ref name=\":5\">{{Cite journal|last=Miles|first=Thomas J.|last2=Cox|first2=Adam B.|date=October 21, 2015|title=Does Immigration Enforcement Reduce Crime? Evidence from Secure Communities|journal=The Journal of Law and Economics|volume=57|issue=4|pages=937\u2013973|doi=10.1086/680935}}</ref><ref name=\":15\">{{Cite journal|last=Baker|first=Scott R.|year=2015|title=Effects of Immigrant Legalization on Crime|journal=American Economic Review|volume=105|issue=5|pages=210\u2013213|doi=10.1257/aer.p20151041|url=https://zenodo.org/record/894372}}</ref><ref name=\":6\" />\n\n===Sanctuary cities===\nCrimes committed by illegal immigrants who had previously been arrested or convicted of crimes have been a focus of particular attention.<ref name=\"LittlefieldDebate\">{{cite news |last1=Littlefield |first1=Christina |title=Sanctuary cities: How Kathryn Steinle's death intensified the immigration debate |url=https://www.latimes.com/local/california/la-me-immigration-sanctuary-kathryn-steinle-20150723-htmlstory.html |accessdate=February 15, 2019 |work=Los Angeles Times |date=July 24, 2015}}</ref><ref name=\"MejiaSpree\">{{cite news |last1=Mejia |first1=Brittany |title=In California's Red Counties, Sheriffs Decry Sanctuary Laws After Crime Spree, Cop Killing |url=http://www.governing.com/topics/public-justice-safety/tns-sanctuary-california-sheriff.html |accessdate=January 22, 2019 | agency= [[Los Angeles Times]] |publisher=[[Governing (magazine)|Governing]] |date=January 3, 2019}}</ref>\n[[Sanctuary cities]]\u2014which adopt policies designed to avoid prosecuting people solely for being in the country illegally\u2014have no statistically meaningful impact on crime, and may reduce the crime rate.<ref name=\":6\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/news/monkey-cage/wp/2016/10/03/sanctuary-cities-do-not-experience-an-increase-in-crime/|title=Sanctuary cities do not experience an increase in crime|last1=Collingwood|first1=Loren|last2=Gonzalez-O'Brien|first2=Benjamin|date=October 3, 2016|website=Washington Post|access-date=October 3, 2016|last3=El-Khatib|first3=Stephen}}</ref><ref name=\":24\">{{Cite journal|last=Mart\u00ednez|first=Daniel E.|last2=Mart\u00ednez-Schuldt|first2=Ricardo D.|last3=Cantor|first3=Guillermo|date=2017|title=Providing Sanctuary or Fostering Crime? A Review of the Research on \"Sanctuary Cities\" and Crime|journal=Sociology Compass|language=en|volume=12|page=e12547|doi=10.1111/soc4.12547|issn=1751-9020}}</ref>\n\nDiscussion has been particularly intense when an illegal alien has been arrested for a minor offense and is known to be in the country illegally is released because the jurisdiction where he was arrested is a [[sanctuary city]] that limits police cooperation with [[U.S. Immigration and Customs Enforcement]] (ICE,) and goes on to commit a new crime.<ref name=\"LittlefieldDebate\"/><ref>{{cite news |last1=CARMEN GEORGE |title=Tulare County sheriff after rampage: Laws should be changed to better communicate with ICE |url=https://www.fresnobee.com/news/local/crime/article223318080.html |accessdate=January 23, 2019 |work=Fresno Bee |date=December 19, 2018 |quote=Garcia-Ruiz has a known criminal past. The sheriff\u2019s office said he received a one-year jail sentence and 36 months probation in 2003, after facing criminal charges in 2002, including armed robbery in Fresno, and assault with a deadly weapon in Reedley.}}</ref> Examples include the 2018 [[Tulare County shootings]], where the suspect had previously served time in American prisons and been deported twice before being arrested on a misdemeanor and released under [[California Sanctuary Law SB54]] the day before he killed two and wounded seven in a [[spree shooting]].<ref name=\"FarzanLaw\">{{cite news |last1=Farzan |first1=Antonia Noori |title=After a shooting suspect's 'reign of terror,' a California sheriff blames the state's sanctuary law |url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/nation/2018/12/20/after-shooting-suspects-reign-terror-california-sheriff-blames-states-sanctuary-law/ |accessdate=January 22, 2019 |work=[[Washington Post]] |date=December 20, 2018}}</ref>\n\n== Laws and regulations ==\n\n=== Special Order 40 (1979) ===\n[[Special Order 40]] is a directive issued jointly by the [[Los Angeles City Council]] and the [[Los Angeles Police Department]] (LAPD) under Chief [[Daryl Gates]] and the [[Los Angeles City Council]] in 1979 prohibiting officers of the LAPD officers from questioning individuals for the sole purpose of whether they were in the United States legally.<ref name=\"DN1\">{{cite news |title=Bratton: Special Order 40 not going anywhere |url=http://www.insidesocal.com/friendlyfire/2008/04/bratton-special-order-40-not-g.html |work=[[Los Angeles Daily News]] |date=April 14, 2008 |author=Mariel Garza |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20081014123547/http://www.insidesocal.com/friendlyfire/2008/04/bratton-special-order-40-not-g.html |archivedate=October 14, 2008 }}</ref> The Special Order was the center of controversy following the 2008 [[Murder of Jamiel Shaw II]] by a perpetrator who was a member of the [[18th Street gang]] and an [[illegal immigration|illegal immigrant]] to the United States.<ref name=\"WintonBlankstein\">{{cite news |last1=Blankstein |first1=Andrew |last2=Winton |first2=Richard |title=Ask and deport, family urges; Their son's alleged killer, in the U.S. illegally, was let out of jail onto the streets. |work=Los Angeles Times |date=April 9, 2008|id={{ProQuest|422206086}} }}</ref><ref name=\"SteinhauerCrusade\">{{cite news |last1=Steinhauer |first1=Jennifer |title=Immigration and Gang Violence Propel Crusade |url=https://www.nytimes.com/2008/05/15/us/15gangs.html |accessdate=February 20, 2019 |work=The New York Times |date=May 15, 2008}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|last=Kim|first=Victoria|url=http://articles.latimes.com/2012/may/10/local/la-me-jamiel-shaw-20120510|title=Gang member convicted of murdering Los Angeles High football star|work=Los Angeles Times|date=May 10, 2012}}</ref><ref name=\"LoweryKilling\">{{cite news |last1=Lowery |first1=Wesley |title=Gang member sentenced to die in star athlete's killing |url=http://articles.latimes.com/2012/nov/02/local/la-me-1103-jamiel-shaw-20121104 |accessdate=February 19, 2019 |publisher=Los Angeles Times |date=November 2, 2012}}</ref>  An effort to put a repeal measure on the ballot in 2009 failed.<ref name=\"WillonBallot\">{{cite news |last1=Willon |first1=Phil |title='Jamiel's Law' misses ballot |url=http://articles.latimes.com/2008/dec/12/local/me-jamiel12 |accessdate=February 19, 2019 |work=Los Angeles Times |date=December 12, 2008}}</ref> Police Commissioner [[William Bratton]] successfully opposed rescinding the Special Order.<ref name=\"DN1\"/>\n\n=== Arizona SB 1070 (2010) ===\nThe ''Support Our Law Enforcement and Safe Neighborhoods Act'' ([[Arizona SB 1070]],) was enacted by the Arizona legislature in 2010 as a response to broad public dislike of illegal immigration among Arizona voters, and by a widespread belief that a great deal of crime was being committed by illegal immigrants that persisted despite a scholarly consensus that illegal immigrants commit proportionately fewer crimes than American citizens.<ref name=\"ArchiboldIdeas\"/>  Public support for the bill was driven by the March 2010 murder of Arizona [[ranch]]er [[Robert Krentz]].<ref name=\"ArchiboldIdeas\">{{cite news |last1=Archibold |first1=Randal |title=On Border Violence, Truth Pales Compared to Ideas |url=https://www.nytimes.com/2010/06/20/us/20crime.html |accessdate=February 18, 2019 |work=The New York Times |date=June 19, 2010}}</ref>\n\n===Texas Senate Bill 4 (2017)===\n[[Texas Senate Bill 4]] was enacted in 2017 to block municipalities in Texas form becoming [[sanctuary cities]], that is, to prevent local authorities from refusing to cooperate with federal authorities in enforcing immigration laws by directing police and court officials not to question persons accused of crimes about their immigration status and to ignore requests by federal authorities to hold individuals who are in the country illegally and have been arrested for minor crimes for deportation.<ref name=\"AbbottSignsBill\">{{cite web | last1=Svitek | first1=Patrick | title=Texas Gov. Greg Abbott Signs \"Sanctuary Cities\" Bill into Law | url=https://www.texastribune.org/2017/05/07/abbott-signs-sanctuary-cities-bill/ | date=May 7, 2017 | publisher=[[The Texas Tribune]] | accessdate=March 26, 2018}}</ref> Texas Senate Bill 4 also allows police officers to check the immigration status of those they detain if they choose.<ref name=\"AbbottSignsBill\"/><ref>{{cite web | last1=Mansoor | first1=Sanya | last2=Pollock | first2=Cassandra | title=Everything You Need to Know About Texas' \"Sanctuary Cities\" Law | url=https://www.texastribune.org/2017/05/08/5-things-know-about-sanctuary-cities-law/ | date=May 8, 2017 | publisher=[[The Texas Tribune]] | accessdate=March 26, 2018}}</ref>\n\n== Political debate ==\n===\u201cTrump Hypothesis\u201d and 2016 Presidential election===\nDuring his presidential campaign [[Donald Trump]] asserted that the immigrants are responsible for higher levels of violent and drug-related crime in the United States. A 2016 study was undertaken to test this hypothesis, specifically with regard to immigrants from [[Mexico]]. According to the study, \"Results largely contradict the Trump Hypothesis: no evidence links Mexican or undocumented Mexican immigrants specifically to violent or [[drug-related crime]].\"<ref>{{Cite journal|last=Green|first=David|date=May 1, 2016|title=The Trump Hypothesis: Testing Immigrant Populations as a Determinant of Violent and Drug-Related Crime in the United States |journal=Social Science Quarterly|volume=97|issue=3|language=en|pages=506\u2013524|doi=10.1111/ssqu.12300|issn=1540-6237}}</ref>\n\nIn July 2015, Donald Trump invited what he terms [[Angel Families]], families who have had a member killed by an illegal immigrant to meet with him. Some had lost relatives in road accidents, others were shot or stabbed, but all had family members who died due to actions taken by what Trump describes as people who never should have been in the U.S. in the first place.  The [[Remembrance Project]], a nonprofit that works to draw attention to the victims of crimes committed by illegal immigrants, helped the campaign locate families of victims.<ref name=\"YeeImmigration\">{{cite news |last1=Yee |first1=Vivian |title=For Grieving Parents, Trump Is 'Speaking for the Dead' on Immigration |url=https://www.nytimes.com/2017/06/25/us/trump-undocumented-victims.html |accessdate=February 20, 2019 |work=The New York Times |date=June 25, 2017}}</ref>\n\nDuring the [[2016 Republican Party presidential primaries]], a [[Act of Love (politics)|political advertisement]] showing mugshots of illegal immigrants who committed violent crimes in the U.S. alternate with footage of candidate [[Jeb Bush]] saying, \"Yeah, they broke the law, but it's not a felony.... It's an [[Act of Love (politics)|act of love]],\"<ref name=\"RichardsonActofLove\">{{cite news|last1=Richardson|first1=Bradford|title=Trump rips Bush over 'act of love' remarks on illegal immigration|url=http://thehill.com/blogs/ballot-box/presidential-races/252325-trump-rips-bush-over-act-of-love-remarks-on-illegal|accessdate=February 24, 2016|work=[[The Hill (newspaper)|The Hill]]|date=August 31, 2015|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160220100558/http://thehill.com/blogs/ballot-box/presidential-races/252325-trump-rips-bush-over-act-of-love-remarks-on-illegal|archivedate=February 20, 2016}}</ref><ref name=\"WarrenActofLove\">{{cite news|last1=Warren|first1=Michael|title=Trump Hits Jeb on 'Act of Love'|url=http://www.weeklystandard.com/trump-hits-jeb-on-act-of-love/article/1023012|accessdate=February 24, 2016|work=The Weekly Standard|date=August 31, 2015}}</ref> is regarded as having played a role in Bush's withdrawal from the race.<ref name=\"SaddiquiBush\">{{cite news|last1=Saddiqui|first1=Sabina|title=Fall of the House of Bush|url=https://www.theguardian.com/us-news/2016/feb/21/jeb-bush-marco-rubio-donald-trump|accessdate=March 24, 2016|work=The Guardian|date=February 21, 2016|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160319120307/http://www.theguardian.com/us-news/2016/feb/21/jeb-bush-marco-rubio-donald-trump|archivedate=March 19, 2016}}</ref>  At a May 2016 campaign rally, Trump told an audience that illegal immigrants  \u201cRaped, sodomized and killed\" Americans.<ref name=\"TanfaniPolls\"/>\n\nJamiel Shaw, Sr., the father of a [[Murder of Jamiel Shaw II|high school student murdered by an illegal immigrant]] in 2008, became a spokesman for the Trump campaign.<ref name=\"McKnightTrail\">{{cite news |last1=McKnight |first1=Michael |title=How the murder of a high school football star became a rallying cry on Trump's campaign trail |url=https://www.si.com/2017/05/02/president-donald-trump-jamiel-shaw-high-school-football-murder |accessdate=February 21, 2019 |publisher=[[Sports Illustrated]] |date=May 2, 2017}}</ref>\n\n=== Presidency ===\nDuring his Presidency, Donald Trump has repeatedly asserted that crimes committed by illegal immigrants to the United States make the construction of a [[Trump wall|wall along the U. S. - Mexico border]] an urgent necessity.  Trump's assertions about crimes committed by illegal immigrants were regularly shown to be inaccurate.<ref name=\"ThomasArizona\">{{cite news |last1=Thomas |first1=Craig |title=KOLD INVESTIGATES: Is MS-13 a problem in southern Arizona? |url=http://www.tucsonnewsnow.com/2019/02/16/kold-investigates-is-ms-problem-southern-arizona/ |accessdate=February 17, 2019 |publisher=[[KOLD-TV]] |date=February 15, 2019}}</ref><ref name=\"RizzoTerrorism\">{{cite news |last1=Rizzo |first1=Salvador |title=The Trump administration's misleading spin on immigration, crime and terrorism |url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/politics/2019/01/07/trump-administrations-misleading-spin-immigration-crime-terrorism/ |accessdate=February 17, 2019 |work=Washington Post |date=January 7, 2019}}</ref>\n\n===2018 midterm election===\n\"One Nation,\" a political nonprofit supporting Republican candidates produced, an ad showing a masked, knife-wielding man with a voice saying, \u201cWe need tough immigration enforcement to keep dangerous criminals out.\u201d<ref name=\"TanfaniPolls\">{{cite news |last1=Tanfani |first1=Joseph |last2=Lange |first2=Jason |last3=Stein |first3=Letitia |title=Special Report: How Republicans are using immigration to scare voters to the polls |url=https://www.reuters.com/article/us-usa-election-immigration-specialrepor-idUSKCN1N018C |accessdate=February 19, 2019 |publisher=Reuters |date=October 26, 2018}}</ref>  Other ads criticized [[sanctuary cities]], something Matt Gorman, spokesman for the National Republican Congressional Committee, said that many Americans oppose.<ref name=\"TanfaniPolls\"/>\n\n==See also==\n*[[Human trafficking in the United States]]\n*[[Operation devil horns]]\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n[[Category:Illegal immigration to the United States]]\n[[Category:Crime in the United States]]\n[[Category:Anti-immigration politics in the United States]]\n", "text_old": "{{lead too short|date=February 2019}}\n{{Use mdy dates|date=March 2019}}\n\nThe issue of crimes committed by [[Illegal immigration to the United States|Illegal immigrants to the United States]] is a topic that is often asserted and debated in politics and the media when discussing [[Immigration policy in the United States]]. According to many studies, undocumented immigrants in the United States are less likely to commit crime than [[Citizenship of the United States|native-born citizens]] and have no impact on violent crime rates.\n\n== Research ==\n\n=== Relationship between immigration status and crime ===\nAccording to empirical evidence, immigrants (including illegal immigrants) are less likely to commit crimes than native-born [[Citizenship of the United States|citizens in the United States]].<ref name=\":25\">{{Cite news|url=http://econofact.org/are-immigrants-more-likely-to-commit-crimes|title=Are immigrants more likely to commit crimes? {{!}} Econofact|date=February 14, 2017|newspaper=Econofact|access-date=February 15, 2017|language=en-US}}</ref><ref name=\":20\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/politics/2017/live-updates/trump-white-house/real-time-fact-checking-and-analysis-of-trumps-address-to-congress/trump-calls-for-creation-of-office-to-support-victims-of-crimes-by-illegal-immigrants/|title=Trump calls for creation of office to support victims of crimes by illegal immigrants|website=Washington Post|access-date=May 4, 2017|quote=On the campaign trail, Trump said he would seek to quickly deport between 2 million and 3 million immigrants with criminal records. But a study by the Migration Policy Institute found that 820,000 unauthorized immigrants had committed other crimes, including about 300,000 with felony records}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.ppic.org/main/publication.asp?i=776|title=Crime, Corrections, and California: What Does Immigration Have to Do with It? (PPIC Publication)|website=www.ppic.org|access-date=June 23, 2016}}</ref><ref name=\":22\">{{Cite journal|last=Gonzalez|first=Benjamin|last2=Collingwood|first2=Loren|last3=El-Khatib|first3=Stephen Omar|date=May 7, 2017|title=The Politics of Refuge: Sanctuary Cities, Crime, and Undocumented Immigration |journal=Urban Affairs Review|volume=55|language=en|doi=10.1177/1078087417704974|page=107808741770497}} Quote: \"most studies have shown that undocumented immigrants tend to commit less crime than the native born\"</ref><ref name=\":21\">{{Cite news|url=http://www.politifact.com/truth-o-meter/statements/2015/jul/06/donald-trump/trump-immigration-claim-has-no-data-back-it/|title=Trump immigration claim has no data to back it up|work=PolitiFact|quote=... every expert we polled said there is a consensus among scholars that undocumented immigrants are not more likely to commit crimes than U.S. citizens.|access-date=August 22, 2017|language=en}}</ref>\n\nA 2018 study found that undocumented immigration to the United States did not increase [[violent crime]] rates.<ref>{{Cite journal|last=Light|first=Michael T.|last2=Miller|first2=TY|title=Does Undocumented Immigration Increase Violent Crime?|journal=Criminology|language=en|volume=56|issue=2|pages=370\u2013401|doi=10.1111/1745-9125.12175|pmid=30464356|pmc=6241529|issn=1745-9125|year=2018}}</ref> A 2017 study found that \"Increased undocumented immigration was significantly associated with reductions in drug arrests, drug overdose deaths, and DUI arrests, net of other factors.\"<ref>{{Cite journal|last=Light|first=Michael T.|last2=Miller|first2=Ty|last3=Kelly|first3=Brian C.|date=July 20, 2017|title=Undocumented Immigration, Drug Problems, and Driving Under the Influence in the United States, 1990\u20132014|journal=American Journal of Public Health|pages=e1\u2013e7|doi=10.2105/AJPH.2017.303884|pmid=28727520|pmc=5551598|issn=0090-0036|volume=107|issue=9}}</ref> A 2017 study found that California's extension of driving licenses to unauthorized immigrants \"did not increase the total number of accidents or the occurrence of fatal accidents, but it did reduce the likelihood of hit and run accidents, thereby improving traffic safety and reducing costs for California drivers ... providing unauthorized immigrants with access to driver's licenses can create positive externalities for the communities in which they live.\"<ref>{{Cite journal|last=Lueders|first=Hans|last2=Hainmueller|first2=Jens|last3=Lawrence|first3=Duncan|date=April 18, 2017|title=Providing driver's licenses to unauthorized immigrants in California improves traffic safety|journal=Proceedings of the National Academy of Sciences|language=en|volume=114|issue=16|pages=4111\u20134116|doi=10.1073/pnas.1618991114|issn=0027-8424|pmid=28373538|pmc=5402447}}</ref>\n\nA 2018 study in the ''[[American Economic Journal|American Economic Journal: Economic Policy]]'' found that by restricting the employment opportunities for unauthorized immigrants, the [[Immigration Reform and Control Act of 1986]] (IRCA) likely caused an increase in crime rates.<ref>{{Cite journal|first=Matthew|last=Freedman|first2=Emily|last2=Owens|first3=Sarah|last3=Bohn|title=Immigration, Employment Opportunities, and Criminal Behavior |journal=American Economic Journal: Economic Policy|volume=10|issue=2|pages=117\u2013151|language=en|doi=10.1257/pol.20150165|issn=1945-7731|year=2018|doi-access=free}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=http://faculty.sites.uci.edu/freedman/files/2017/06/FreedmanOwensBohn_Manuscript.pdf|title=Immigration, Employment Opportunities, and Criminal Behavior|last=|first=|date=|website=|access-date=}}</ref> A 2018 ''[[PLOS One]]'' study estimated that the undocumented immigrant population in the United States was 22 million, approximately twice as large as the estimate derived from the\n[[United States Census Bureau]]'s figures. An author of the study notes that this has implications for the relationship between undocumented immigration and crime, suggesting that the crime rate among undocumented immigrants is significantly lower than previously estimated: \"You have the same number of crimes but now spread over twice as many people as was believed before, which right away means that the crime rate among undocumented immigrants is essentially half whatever was previously believed.\"<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://thehill.com/latino/407848-yale-mit-study-22-million-not-11-million-undocumented-immigrants-in-us|title=Yale, MIT study: 22 million, not 11 million, undocumented immigrants in US|last=Garcia|first=Eric|date=September 21, 2018|website=TheHill|language=en|access-date=December 28, 2018}}</ref>\n\nAccording to analysis of the [[2010 United States Census]], \"immigrants to the United States are significantly less likely than native-born citizens to be incarcerated. The authors found that 1.6 percent of immigrant males age 18-39 are incarcerated, compared to 3.3 percent of the native-born... The divide was even sharper when the authors examined the incarceration rate among immigrant men the authors believe likely to be undocumented \u2014 specifically less-educated men from [[El Salvador]] and [[Guatemala]] between age 18-29. ... According to the analysis, these likely undocumented immigrants had an incarceration rate of 1.7 percent, compared with 10.7 percent for native-born men without a high school diploma\".<ref>{{cite news |last1=JULIA DAHL |title=How big a problem is crime committed by immigrants? |url=https://www.cbsnews.com/news/illegal-immigrants-and-crime-how-big-a-problem-is-crime-committed-by-immigrants/ |accessdate=February 23, 2019 |work=CBS News |date=January 27, 2017 |quote=}}</ref>\n\nA 2018 study found no evidence that apprehensions of undocumented immigrants in districts in the United States reduced crime rates.<ref>{{Cite journal|last=|first=|date=2018|title=Do Apprehensions of Undocumented Immigrants Reduce Crime and Create Jobs? Evidence from U.S. Districts, 2000-2015|url=https://lawreview.law.ucdavis.edu/issues/52/1/Symposium/52-1_Hines_Peri.pdf|journal=UC Davis Law Review|volume=|pages=|via=}}</ref>\n\nAccording to immigration analyst [[Alex Nowrasteh]], and criminologist [[Barry Latzer]], [[Texas]] is the only state that tracks illegal immigrants by the specific crime committed.<ref name=\"NowrastehCrime\"/><ref name=\"NowrastehRate\"/><ref name=\"LatzerRates\">{{cite news |last1=Latzer |first1=Barry |title=Do Illegal Aliens Have High Crime Rates? |url=https://www.city-journal.org/illegal-alien-crime-rate-data |accessdate=February 28, 2019 |publisher=[[City Journal]] |date=January 24, 2019}}</ref>  Homicide data are regarded as more accurate than data on other crimes because \"a much higher proportion of murders are solved.\"<ref name=\"LatzerRates\"/> The Texas data for 2016 showed that the rate of murder convictions in 2016 was 3.2 per 100,000 native-born Americans, 0.9 for every 100,000 legal immigrants and 1.8 per 100,000 illegal immigrants.<ref name=\"NowrastehCrime\">{{cite news |last1=Nowrasteh |first1=Alex |title=The Murder of Mollie Tibbetts and Illegal Immigrant Crime |url=https://www.cato.org/blog/murder-mollie-tibbetts-illegal-immigrant-crime-facts |accessdate=February 15, 2019 |publisher=[[Cato Institute]] |date=August 22, 2018}}</ref><ref name=\"NowrastehRate\">{{cite news |last1=Nowrasteh |first1=Alez |title=Everything is Bigger in Texas \u2014 except the illegal immigrant crime rate |url=https://www.houstonchronicle.com/opinion/outlook/article/Everything-is-Bigger-in-Texas-Except-the-12747805.php |accessdate=February 15, 2019 |work=Houston Chronicle |date=March 12, 2018}}</ref>\n\n===Others===\nA 2016 study of an effort to reduce crime in [[North Carolina]] by identifying and deporting illegal immigrants showed no correlation between increased deportation enforcement and local crime rates.<ref>Forrester, Andrew, and Alex Nowrasteh. Do Immigration Enforcement Programs Reduce Crime?: Evidence from the 287(g) Program in North Carolina. Cato Institute, 2018, www.jstor.org/stable/resrep16983.</ref>\n\n==Procedures==\nIndividuals who are in the United States illegally and who have been convicted of crimes are eligible to be deported under federal law.{{citation needed|date=March 2019}} Research suggests that immigration enforcement has no impact on crime rates.<ref name=\":5\">{{Cite journal|last=Miles|first=Thomas J.|last2=Cox|first2=Adam B.|date=October 21, 2015|title=Does Immigration Enforcement Reduce Crime? Evidence from Secure Communities|journal=The Journal of Law and Economics|volume=57|issue=4|pages=937\u2013973|doi=10.1086/680935}}</ref><ref name=\":15\">{{Cite journal|last=Baker|first=Scott R.|year=2015|title=Effects of Immigrant Legalization on Crime|journal=American Economic Review|volume=105|issue=5|pages=210\u2013213|doi=10.1257/aer.p20151041|url=https://zenodo.org/record/894372}}</ref><ref name=\":6\" />\n\n===Sanctuary cities===\nCrimes committed by illegal immigrants who had previously been arrested or convicted of crimes have been a focus of particular attention.<ref name=\"LittlefieldDebate\">{{cite news |last1=Littlefield |first1=Christina |title=Sanctuary cities: How Kathryn Steinle's death intensified the immigration debate |url=https://www.latimes.com/local/california/la-me-immigration-sanctuary-kathryn-steinle-20150723-htmlstory.html |accessdate=February 15, 2019 |work=Los Angeles Times |date=July 24, 2015}}</ref><ref name=\"MejiaSpree\">{{cite news |last1=Mejia |first1=Brittany |title=In California's Red Counties, Sheriffs Decry Sanctuary Laws After Crime Spree, Cop Killing |url=http://www.governing.com/topics/public-justice-safety/tns-sanctuary-california-sheriff.html |accessdate=January 22, 2019 | agency= [[Los Angeles Times]] |publisher=[[Governing (magazine)|Governing]] |date=January 3, 2019}}</ref>\n[[Sanctuary cities]]\u2014which adopt policies designed to avoid prosecuting people solely for being in the country illegally\u2014have no statistically meaningful impact on crime, and may reduce the crime rate.<ref name=\":6\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/news/monkey-cage/wp/2016/10/03/sanctuary-cities-do-not-experience-an-increase-in-crime/|title=Sanctuary cities do not experience an increase in crime|last1=Collingwood|first1=Loren|last2=Gonzalez-O'Brien|first2=Benjamin|date=October 3, 2016|website=Washington Post|access-date=October 3, 2016|last3=El-Khatib|first3=Stephen}}</ref><ref name=\":24\">{{Cite journal|last=Mart\u00ednez|first=Daniel E.|last2=Mart\u00ednez-Schuldt|first2=Ricardo D.|last3=Cantor|first3=Guillermo|date=2017|title=Providing Sanctuary or Fostering Crime? A Review of the Research on \"Sanctuary Cities\" and Crime|journal=Sociology Compass|language=en|volume=12|page=e12547|doi=10.1111/soc4.12547|issn=1751-9020}}</ref>\n\nDiscussion has been particularly intense when an illegal alien has been arrested for a minor offense and is known to be in the country illegally is released because the jurisdiction where he was arrested is a [[sanctuary city]] that limits police cooperation with [[U.S. Immigration and Customs Enforcement]] (ICE,) and goes on to commit a new crime.<ref name=\"LittlefieldDebate\"/><ref>{{cite news |last1=CARMEN GEORGE |title=Tulare County sheriff after rampage: Laws should be changed to better communicate with ICE |url=https://www.fresnobee.com/news/local/crime/article223318080.html |accessdate=January 23, 2019 |work=Fresno Bee |date=December 19, 2018 |quote=Garcia-Ruiz has a known criminal past. The sheriff\u2019s office said he received a one-year jail sentence and 36 months probation in 2003, after facing criminal charges in 2002, including armed robbery in Fresno, and assault with a deadly weapon in Reedley.}}</ref> Examples include the 2018 [[Tulare County shootings]], where the suspect had previously served time in American prisons and been deported twice before being arrested on a misdemeanor and released under [[California Sanctuary Law SB54]] the day before he killed two and wounded seven in a [[spree shooting]].<ref name=\"FarzanLaw\">{{cite news |last1=Farzan |first1=Antonia Noori |title=After a shooting suspect's 'reign of terror,' a California sheriff blames the state's sanctuary law |url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/nation/2018/12/20/after-shooting-suspects-reign-terror-california-sheriff-blames-states-sanctuary-law/ |accessdate=January 22, 2019 |work=[[Washington Post]] |date=December 20, 2018}}</ref>\n\n== Laws and regulations ==\n\n=== Special Order 40 (1979) ===\n[[Special Order 40]] is a directive issued jointly by the [[Los Angeles City Council]] and the [[Los Angeles Police Department]] (LAPD) under Chief [[Daryl Gates]] and the [[Los Angeles City Council]] in 1979 prohibiting officers of the LAPD officers from questioning individuals for the sole purpose of whether they were in the United States legally.<ref name=\"DN1\">{{cite news |title=Bratton: Special Order 40 not going anywhere |url=http://www.insidesocal.com/friendlyfire/2008/04/bratton-special-order-40-not-g.html |work=[[Los Angeles Daily News]] |date=April 14, 2008 |author=Mariel Garza |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20081014123547/http://www.insidesocal.com/friendlyfire/2008/04/bratton-special-order-40-not-g.html |archivedate=October 14, 2008 }}</ref> The Special Order was the center of controversy following the 2008 [[Murder of Jamiel Shaw II]] by a perpetrator who was a member of the [[18th Street gang]] and an [[illegal immigration|illegal immigrant]] to the United States.<ref name=\"WintonBlankstein\">{{cite news |last1=Blankstein |first1=Andrew |last2=Winton |first2=Richard |title=Ask and deport, family urges; Their son's alleged killer, in the U.S. illegally, was let out of jail onto the streets. |work=Los Angeles Times |date=April 9, 2008|id={{ProQuest|422206086}} }}</ref><ref name=\"SteinhauerCrusade\">{{cite news |last1=Steinhauer |first1=Jennifer |title=Immigration and Gang Violence Propel Crusade |url=https://www.nytimes.com/2008/05/15/us/15gangs.html |accessdate=February 20, 2019 |work=The New York Times |date=May 15, 2008}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|last=Kim|first=Victoria|url=http://articles.latimes.com/2012/may/10/local/la-me-jamiel-shaw-20120510|title=Gang member convicted of murdering Los Angeles High football star|work=Los Angeles Times|date=May 10, 2012}}</ref><ref name=\"LoweryKilling\">{{cite news |last1=Lowery |first1=Wesley |title=Gang member sentenced to die in star athlete's killing |url=http://articles.latimes.com/2012/nov/02/local/la-me-1103-jamiel-shaw-20121104 |accessdate=February 19, 2019 |publisher=Los Angeles Times |date=November 2, 2012}}</ref>  An effort to put a repeal measure on the ballot in 2009 failed.<ref name=\"WillonBallot\">{{cite news |last1=Willon |first1=Phil |title='Jamiel's Law' misses ballot |url=http://articles.latimes.com/2008/dec/12/local/me-jamiel12 |accessdate=February 19, 2019 |work=Los Angeles Times |date=December 12, 2008}}</ref> Police Commissioner [[William Bratton]] successfully opposed rescinding the Special Order.<ref name=\"DN1\"/>\n\n=== Arizona SB 1070 (2010) ===\nThe ''Support Our Law Enforcement and Safe Neighborhoods Act'' ([[Arizona SB 1070]],) was enacted by the Arizona legislature in 2010 as a response to broad public dislike of illegal immigration among Arizona voters, and by a widespread belief that a great deal of crime was being committed by illegal immigrants that persisted despite a scholarly consensus that illegal immigrants commit proportionately fewer crimes than American citizens.<ref name=\"ArchiboldIdeas\"/>  Public support for the bill was driven by the March 2010 murder of Arizona [[ranch]]er [[Robert Krentz]].<ref name=\"ArchiboldIdeas\">{{cite news |last1=Archibold |first1=Randal |title=On Border Violence, Truth Pales Compared to Ideas |url=https://www.nytimes.com/2010/06/20/us/20crime.html |accessdate=February 18, 2019 |work=The New York Times |date=June 19, 2010}}</ref>\n\n===Texas Senate Bill 4 (2017)===\n[[Texas Senate Bill 4]] was enacted in 2017 to block municipalities in Texas form becoming [[sanctuary cities]], that is, to prevent local authorities from refusing to cooperate with federal authorities in enforcing immigration laws by directing police and court officials not to question persons accused of crimes about their immigration status and to ignore requests by federal authorities to hold individuals who are in the country illegally and have been arrested for minor crimes for deportation.<ref name=\"AbbottSignsBill\">{{cite web | last1=Svitek | first1=Patrick | title=Texas Gov. Greg Abbott Signs \"Sanctuary Cities\" Bill into Law | url=https://www.texastribune.org/2017/05/07/abbott-signs-sanctuary-cities-bill/ | date=May 7, 2017 | publisher=[[The Texas Tribune]] | accessdate=March 26, 2018}}</ref> Texas Senate Bill 4 also allows police officers to check the immigration status of those they detain if they choose.<ref name=\"AbbottSignsBill\"/><ref>{{cite web | last1=Mansoor | first1=Sanya | last2=Pollock | first2=Cassandra | title=Everything You Need to Know About Texas' \"Sanctuary Cities\" Law | url=https://www.texastribune.org/2017/05/08/5-things-know-about-sanctuary-cities-law/ | date=May 8, 2017 | publisher=[[The Texas Tribune]] | accessdate=March 26, 2018}}</ref>\n\n== Political debate ==\n===\u201cTrump Hypothesis\u201d and 2016 Presidential election===\nDuring his presidential campaign [[Donald Trump]] asserted that the immigrants are responsible for higher levels of violent and drug-related crime in the United States. A 2016 study was undertaken to test this hypothesis, specifically with regard to immigrants from [[Mexico]]. According to the study, \"Results largely contradict the Trump Hypothesis: no evidence links Mexican or undocumented Mexican immigrants specifically to violent or [[drug-related crime]].\"<ref>{{Cite journal|last=Green|first=David|date=May 1, 2016|title=The Trump Hypothesis: Testing Immigrant Populations as a Determinant of Violent and Drug-Related Crime in the United States |journal=Social Science Quarterly|volume=97|issue=3|language=en|pages=506\u2013524|doi=10.1111/ssqu.12300|issn=1540-6237}}</ref>\n\nIn July 2015, Donald Trump invited what he terms [[Angel Families]], families who have had a member killed by an illegal immigrant to meet with him. Some had lost relatives in road accidents, others were shot or stabbed, but all had family members who died due to actions taken by what Trump describes as people who never should have been in the U.S. in the first place.  The [[Remembrance Project]], a nonprofit that works to draw attention to the victims of crimes committed by illegal immigrants, helped the campaign locate families of victims.<ref name=\"YeeImmigration\">{{cite news |last1=Yee |first1=Vivian |title=For Grieving Parents, Trump Is 'Speaking for the Dead' on Immigration |url=https://www.nytimes.com/2017/06/25/us/trump-undocumented-victims.html |accessdate=February 20, 2019 |work=The New York Times |date=June 25, 2017}}</ref>\n\nDuring the [[2016 Republican Party presidential primaries]], a [[Act of Love (politics)|political advertisement]] showing mugshots of illegal immigrants who committed violent crimes in the U.S. alternate with footage of candidate [[Jeb Bush]] saying, \"Yeah, they broke the law, but it's not a felony.... It's an [[Act of Love (politics)|act of love]],\"<ref name=\"RichardsonActofLove\">{{cite news|last1=Richardson|first1=Bradford|title=Trump rips Bush over 'act of love' remarks on illegal immigration|url=http://thehill.com/blogs/ballot-box/presidential-races/252325-trump-rips-bush-over-act-of-love-remarks-on-illegal|accessdate=February 24, 2016|work=[[The Hill (newspaper)|The Hill]]|date=August 31, 2015|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160220100558/http://thehill.com/blogs/ballot-box/presidential-races/252325-trump-rips-bush-over-act-of-love-remarks-on-illegal|archivedate=February 20, 2016}}</ref><ref name=\"WarrenActofLove\">{{cite news|last1=Warren|first1=Michael|title=Trump Hits Jeb on 'Act of Love'|url=http://www.weeklystandard.com/trump-hits-jeb-on-act-of-love/article/1023012|accessdate=February 24, 2016|work=The Weekly Standard|date=August 31, 2015}}</ref> is regarded as having played a role in Bush's withdrawal from the race.<ref name=\"SaddiquiBush\">{{cite news|last1=Saddiqui|first1=Sabina|title=Fall of the House of Bush|url=https://www.theguardian.com/us-news/2016/feb/21/jeb-bush-marco-rubio-donald-trump|accessdate=March 24, 2016|work=The Guardian|date=February 21, 2016|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160319120307/http://www.theguardian.com/us-news/2016/feb/21/jeb-bush-marco-rubio-donald-trump|archivedate=March 19, 2016}}</ref>  At a May 2016 campaign rally, Trump told an audience that illegal immigrants  \u201cRaped, sodomized and killed\" Americans.<ref name=\"TanfaniPolls\"/>\n\nJamiel Shaw, Sr., the father of a [[Murder of Jamiel Shaw II|high school student murdered by an illegal immigrant]] in 2008, became a spokesman for the Trump campaign.<ref name=\"McKnightTrail\">{{cite news |last1=McKnight |first1=Michael |title=How the murder of a high school football star became a rallying cry on Trump's campaign trail |url=https://www.si.com/2017/05/02/president-donald-trump-jamiel-shaw-high-school-football-murder |accessdate=February 21, 2019 |publisher=[[Sports Illustrated]] |date=May 2, 2017}}</ref>\n\n=== Presidency ===\nDuring his Presidency, Donald Trump has repeatedly asserted that crimes committed by illegal immigrants to the United States make the construction of a [[Trump wall|wall along the U. S. - Mexico border]] an urgent necessity.  Trump's assertions about crimes committed by illegal immigrants were regularly shown to be inaccurate.<ref name=\"ThomasArizona\">{{cite news |last1=Thomas |first1=Craig |title=KOLD INVESTIGATES: Is MS-13 a problem in southern Arizona? |url=http://www.tucsonnewsnow.com/2019/02/16/kold-investigates-is-ms-problem-southern-arizona/ |accessdate=February 17, 2019 |publisher=[[KOLD-TV]] |date=February 15, 2019}}</ref><ref name=\"RizzoTerrorism\">{{cite news |last1=Rizzo |first1=Salvador |title=The Trump administration's misleading spin on immigration, crime and terrorism |url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/politics/2019/01/07/trump-administrations-misleading-spin-immigration-crime-terrorism/ |accessdate=February 17, 2019 |work=Washington Post |date=January 7, 2019}}</ref>\n\n===2018 midterm election===\n\"One Nation,\" a political nonprofit supporting Republican candidates produced, an ad showing a masked, knife-wielding man with a voice saying, \u201cWe need tough immigration enforcement to keep dangerous criminals out.\u201d<ref name=\"TanfaniPolls\">{{cite news |last1=Tanfani |first1=Joseph |last2=Lange |first2=Jason |last3=Stein |first3=Letitia |title=Special Report: How Republicans are using immigration to scare voters to the polls |url=https://www.reuters.com/article/us-usa-election-immigration-specialrepor-idUSKCN1N018C |accessdate=February 19, 2019 |publisher=Reuters |date=October 26, 2018}}</ref>  Other ads criticized [[sanctuary cities]], something Matt Gorman, spokesman for the National Republican Congressional Committee, said that many Americans oppose.<ref name=\"TanfaniPolls\"/>\n\n==See also==\n*[[Human trafficking in the United States]]\n*[[Operation devil horns]]\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n[[Category:Illegal immigration to the United States]]\n[[Category:Crime in the United States]]\n[[Category:Anti-immigration politics in the United States]]\n", "name_user": "FETJONS", "label": "safe", "comment": "removed inaccurate information", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Illegal_immigration_to_the_United_States_and_crime"}
{"title_page": "Ten Percent Ring", "text_new": "The '''Ten-Percent Ring''' was a title given by the editors of ''[[The Tombstone Epitaph]]'' in 1881 to [[Johnny Behan]] and his friends for stealing about ten percent of the local [[Tombstone, Arizona]] taxes in the 1880s. Milt Joyce, owner of the Oriental Saloon and chairman of [[Cochise County, Arizona]] supervisors was also seen as a leader of the Ten Percent Ring. The ''Tombstone Epitaph'' was started by [[John Clum]] in 1880. <ref>The Tombstone Epitaph, December 25, 1881.</ref> The newspaper outlined the corruption charges of Johnny Behan the Cochise County [[sheriff]]. <ref>James Covington Hancock Papers, Arizona Historical Society, Tucson.</ref> <ref>Wyatt Earp: A Vigilante Life, Andrew C. Isenberg page 241</ref> When Johnny Behan was the Cochise County sheriff one of his duties was collecting prostitution, gambling, liquor, and theater taxes. As part of his pay, he received 10% of all proceeds collected. There was much talk in the town about the [[Graft (politics)|graft]] [[political corruption]] of the sheriff. For this many saw Behan as the head of the Ten Percent Ring and a friend of the outlaw [[Cochise County Cowboys]]. Others accused of members of the ring was Artemus Fay, owner of the Tombstone's first newspaper, the ''Tombstone Nugget'' and Harry Wood a writer for the ''Nugget'' and an under-sheriff of Behan. Behan so focuseded on taxes, that he was very soft on crime. Soon after Behan became sheriff, [[Virgil Earp]] was appointed Tombstone city marshal and had is brothers [[Wyatt Earp]] and [[Morgan Earp]] become special deputy policemen. Behan and the Earps were at conflict as Behan supported the outlaw [[Ike Clanton|Clanton]] and [[Frank McLaury|McLaury]] families.<ref>{{cite book|last=Urban|first=William|title=Wyatt Earp: The O.K. Corral and the Law of the American West |year=2003|publisher=The Rosen Publishing Group, Inc|url=https://archive.org/details/wyattearpokcorra00urba|url-access=registration|page=[https://archive.org/details/wyattearpokcorra00urba/page/67 67]}}</ref><ref name=butler /> On January 31, 1882, Behan was arrested for collecting bills totaling $300 twice, arraigned in front of [[William Henry Stilwell|Justice Stilwell]], and discharged due to a technicality.<ref name=union14140>{{cite web|publisher=Sacramento Daily Union|volume=14 |number=140 |date=2 February 1882 |accessdate=16 October 2014 |title=Discharged from Custody Cowboys Surrendered|url=http://cdnc.ucr.edu/cgi-bin/cdnc?a=d&d=SDU18820202.2.7.3&srpos=48&e=-------en--20--41--txt-txIN-tombstone+earp------#}}</ref> Behan failed to win re-election as sheriff in November of 1882, he would not serve as a peace officer again. He later was appointed as the warden of the [[Yuma Territorial Prison]] and had various other government jobs until his death in 1912.<ref>[https://www.geni.com/people/Johnny-Behan-Sheriff-Cochise-County-Arizona-Territory/6000000010967709781 geni.com Johnny Behan] </ref><ref>Murder in Tombstone: The Forgotten Trial of Wyatt Earp, By Steven Lubet, page 38</ref><ref>I Meet Mrs. Earp, I Married Wyatt Earp, by Josephine Sarah Marcus Earp. Edited by Glenn G. Boyer. Tucson: University of Arizona Press, 1976.</ref><ref name=butler>{{cite book|last=Butler|first=Anne M.|title=Daughters of Joy, Sisters of Misery: Prostitutes in the American West, 1865\u201390|year=1987|publisher=University of Illinois Press|location=Urbana, Ill.|isbn=978-0-252-01466-6|edition=paperback|url=https://archive.org/details/daughtersofjoysi00butl}}</ref><ref>Doc Holliday: The Life and Legend, By Gary L. Roberts, page </ref> Milt Joyce, departed Tombstone in 1883. On October 10, 1880 Joyce and [[Doc Holliday]] had a shoot out at the Oriental. Joyce died in 1889 at the age of 42 in [[San Francisco]], he was the owner of the Baldwin Billiard Parlor in 1883 and later the Cafe Royal in San Francisco.<ref>[http://www.americancowboychronicles.com/2019/12/milt-joyce-western-pioneer.html americancowboychronicles.com Milt Joyce]</ref><ref>The Daily Alta California, November 30th, 1889</ref>\n\n==Popular culture==\nThe Ten Percent Ring was a key figure in the much-fictionized TV series ''[[The Life and Legend of Wyatt Earp]]'', starring [[Hugh O'Brian]] in the starring role. [[Steve Brodie (actor)|Steve Brodie]] played Behan in nine episodes of the series.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.imdb.com/name/nm0479017/?ref_=tt_cl_t9|title=Lash LaRue|publisher=[[Internet Movie Data Base]]|accessdate=10 August 2013}}</ref>\n\n==See also==\n*[[Gunfight at the O.K. Corral]]\n*[[Confederate Arizona]]\n*[[Arizona Territory in the American Civil War]]\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n{{Cochise County, Arizona}}\n{{Wild West}}\n{{Cochise County Conflict}}\n\n\n[[Category:History of Cochise County, Arizona]]\n[[Category:Arizona folklore]]\n[[Category:Crime in Arizona Territory]]\n[[Category:Conflicts in 1881]]\n[[Category:Cochise County conflict]]\n[[Category:Outlaws of the American Old West]]\n[[Category:Gangs in Arizona]]\n", "text_old": "The '''Ten-Percent Ring''' was a title given by the editors of ''[[The Tombstone Epitaph]]'' in 1881 to [[Johnny Behan]] and his friends for stealing about ten percent of the local [[Tombstone, Arizona]] taxes in the 1880s. Milt Joyce, owner of the Oriental Saloon and chairman of [[Cochise County, Arizona]] supervisors was also seen as a leader of the Ten Percent Ring. The ''Tombstone Epitaph'' was started by [[John Clum]] in 1880. <ref>The Tombstone Epitaph, December 25, 1881.</ref> The newspaper outlined the corruption charges of Johnny Behan the Cochise County [[sheriff]]. <ref>James Covington Hancock Papers, Arizona Historical Society, Tucson.</ref> <ref>Wyatt Earp: A Vigilante Life, Andrew C. Isenberg page 241</ref> When Johnny Behan was the Cochise County sheriff one of his duties was collecting prostitution, gambling, liquor, and theater taxes. As part of his pay, he received 10% of all proceeds collected. There was much talk in the town about the [[Graft (politics)|graft]] [[political corruption]] of the sheriff. For this many saw Behan as the head of the Ten Percent Ring and a friend of the outlaw [[Cochise County Cowboys]]. Others accused of members of the ring was Artemus Fay, owner of the Tombstone's first newspaper, the ''Tombstone Nugget'' and Harry Wood a writer for the ''Nugget'' and an under-sheriff of Behan. Behan so focuseded on taxes, that he was very soft on crime. Soon after Behan became sheriff, [[Virgil Earp]] was appointed Tombstone city marshal and had is brothers [[Wyatt Earp]] and [[Morgan Earp]] become special deputy policemen. Behan and the Earps were at conflict as Behan supported the outlaw [[Ike Clanton|Clanton]] and [[Frank McLaury|McLaury]] families.<ref>{{cite book|last=Urban|first=William|title=Wyatt Earp: The O.K. Corral and the Law of the American West |year=2003|publisher=The Rosen Publishing Group, Inc|url=https://archive.org/details/wyattearpokcorra00urba|url-access=registration|page=[https://archive.org/details/wyattearpokcorra00urba/page/67 67]}}</ref><ref name=butler /> On January 31, 1882, Behan was arrested for collecting bills totaling $300 twice, arraigned in front of [[William Henry Stilwell|Justice Stilwell]], and discharged due to a technicality.<ref name=union14140>{{cite web|publisher=Sacramento Daily Union|volume=14 |number=140 |date=2 February 1882 |accessdate=16 October 2014 |title=Discharged from Custody Cowboys Surrendered|url=http://cdnc.ucr.edu/cgi-bin/cdnc?a=d&d=SDU18820202.2.7.3&srpos=48&e=-------en--20--41--txt-txIN-tombstone+earp------#}}</ref> Behan failed to win re-election as sheriff in November of 1882, he would not serve as a peace officer again. He later was appointed as the warden of the [[Yuma Territorial Prison]] and had various other government jobs until his death in 1912.<ref>[https://www.geni.com/people/Johnny-Behan-Sheriff-Cochise-County-Arizona-Territory/6000000010967709781 geni.com Johnny Behan] </ref><ref>Murder in Tombstone: The Forgotten Trial of Wyatt Earp, By Steven Lubet, page 38</ref><ref>I Meet Mrs. Earp, I Married Wyatt Earp, by Josephine Sarah Marcus Earp. Edited by Glenn G. Boyer. Tucson: University of Arizona Press, 1976.</ref><ref name=butler>{{cite book|last=Butler|first=Anne M.|title=Daughters of Joy, Sisters of Misery: Prostitutes in the American West, 1865\u201390|year=1987|publisher=University of Illinois Press|location=Urbana, Ill.|isbn=978-0-252-01466-6|edition=paperback|url=https://archive.org/details/daughtersofjoysi00butl}}</ref><ref>Doc Holliday: The Life and Legend, By Gary L. Roberts, page </ref> Milt Joyce, departed Tombstone in 1883. On October 10, 1880 Joyce and [[Doc Holliday]] had a shoot out at the Oriental. Joyce died in 1889 at the age of 42 in [[San Francisco]], he was the owner of the Baldwin Billiard Parlor in 1883 and later the Cafe Royal in San Francisco.<ref>[http://www.americancowboychronicles.com/2019/12/milt-joyce-western-pioneer.html americancowboychronicles.com Milt Joyce]</ref><ref>The Daily Alta California, November 30th, 1889</ref>\n\n==Popular culture==\nThe Ten Percent Ring was a key figure in the much-fictionized TV series ''[[The Life and Legend of Wyatt Earp]]'', starring [[Hugh O'Brian]] in the starring role. [[Steve Brodie (actor)|Steve Brodie]] played Behan in nine episodes of the series.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.imdb.com/name/nm0479017/?ref_=tt_cl_t9|title=Lash LaRue|publisher=[[Internet Movie Data Base]]|accessdate=10 August 2013}}</ref>\n\n==See also==\n*[[Gunfight at the O.K. Corral]]\n*[[Confederate Arizona]]\n*[[Arizona Territory in the American Civil War]]\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n[[Category:History of Cochise County, Arizona]]\n[[Category:Arizona folklore]]\n[[Category:Crime in Arizona Territory]]\n[[Category:Conflicts in 1881]]\n[[Category:Cochise County conflict]]\n[[Category:Outlaws of the American Old West]]\n[[Category:Gangs in Arizona]]\n", "name_user": "Telecineguy", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eRef